Equating the integrated gate and integrated release seems bizarre to me

IMO we want to evolve the gate because it's proving to be unsustainable in a bunch of ways. I think the ideas here for changing the gate are great, and we should be up for trying lots of different things. This is a pretty new idea in open-source development practices, of course we'll need to evolve it.

On the other hand, I think the release works very well (particularly for the projects themselves, the release team and distros) and see absolutely no direct relationship between the configuration of the gate and the makeup of the release. We can go over again the rationale for a release process like this, but I'd see that as a distraction from the issue of the gate. I don't think the release model needs to be evolved with the kind of urgency that the gate needs.

Repeating http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-September/046653.html but, the other two areas I think we're falling down are ...

Serving operators by providing information that is useful to them. Jay describes those information needs well in his blog post suggesting tags. Futzing about with the contents of the integrated release is not going to provide operators with that information.

Serving end users by driving real interoperability. DefCore's refstack testing infrastructure seems to be the only real progress being made there."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-03 09:02:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-10-03 10:14:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I think we need to stop calling that "the integrated release". "Integrated release" is an overloaded term which, being the ultimate Grail of our project structure, means different things depending on the stakeholder you talk to. Changing what it means but keeping the same terminology is IMHO a recipe for more confusion down the road.

In particular, "integrated release" currently means "valuable thing" for almost all stakeholders, so anything thrown out of it will resist the change.

I like to think of the Ring0 as a production artifact. It's an arbitrary set of projects (defined based on an opinionated use case), but they are (1) highly interdependent, (2) all fine with stronger alignment and TC direction/oversight, (3) all current horizontal teams seem fine supporting them, and (4) unlikely to dramatically increase in size, so sustainable for those said horizontal teams. So it's a group of projects and horizontal teams that are fine working together, under increased control of the TC. It's not a statement of value, it's just a production structure.

It's perfectly fine to me if another group of OpenStack projects decide to have shared services (other horizontal teams) and call themselves "RingB".

In summary, using "integrated release" to describe Ring0 makes it unique and valuable. It's just a set of projects submitting themselves to increased constraints, and a number of people lined up to support that same set. Nothing more. Making it artificially valuable won't give us anything.'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-10-03 10:53:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I can't see the need to conflate these two definitional aspects of the Integrated release:

* the integrated release is a selection of projects that address a specific narrow use-case (booting a VM)
* the integrated release is gated in certain way and provides certain points of contact for cross-project concerns

Why would rationalizing the degree of co-gating between projects require us to scale down the integrated release to this minimal blessed subset?

My essential question about all of this ... is the core problem here a design flaw in the gate that led to a combinatorial explosion of co-gating complexity?

If so, why don't we just simply go fix that?

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-10-03 12:21:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

The integrated release is not just about constraints of gate resources. It's constraints of horizontal teams - QA, Docs, Release Management, Vulnerability Management."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-10-03 12:22:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

And stable maint.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-03 14:14:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(6 comments)'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-03 14:19:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Sean - Good point. How should we call that out?'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-03 14:20:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Eoghan - The set of projects required to boot a VM will, eventually, be smaller than the integrated release. The projects are listed separately so we can discuss both sets as different things, assuming we like the definition of the integrated release as being based on what tests against the compute core or whatever we call it.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-03 14:30:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Thierry - I agree it would be better to have an alternate name, but I don't think "layer 1" or "ring 0" are descriptive enough to anyone outside of the project.

I'm less certain there is broad agreement this grouping is just a "production artifact." As you say, there are some quite strong statements from cross-project teams that they want to be able to focus on a subset of the projects, and not be expected to participate in the others. It seems that whatever we call this special group of projects, by designating them as a group at all we will be saying that they are going to have that attention and anything outside of the list will not. That's not an artifact, that's an explicit approval of the allocation of resources.

I'm not entirely comfortable with that, and would prefer that we instead require projects to add a contributor to each cross-project team before being granted status, but one of the reasons I agreed to undertake writing all of this up was to try to understand fully the implications of the proposals others had put forward, and that wasn't part of any of them.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-03 14:32:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Mark - My understanding of the relationship-based approach is to find some sort of logical basis for drawing a line for resource allocation. Beyond that, I'm going to have to let Monty, Devananda, and Jay comment because this is based mostly on their work."}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-10-03 16:25:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Sean: sure, it's the interaction with the entirety of the cross-project concerns, but the question is which *subset* of those concerns is under strain to breaking point and thus driving these proposed changes?

i.e. I assume we're not saying the stable-maint effort is so overloaded that the stable-maint team is crying out for a smaller integrated release."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-10-06 19:20:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(6 comments)

I don't believe there should be a thing called "the OpenStack integrated release". Instead, I believe there should be a set of tags that are applied to projects in the openstack/ code namespace that indicate the release cadence they follow, the testing contracts they abide with, the cross-project integration points they depend on, etc.

Best,

-jay'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-06 19:29:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-10-09 19:13:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)

Totally agree with markmc here.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-10-10 09:39:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Doug: I would replace this by a definition of the new "Compute Base Ring" concept. You can keep most of the words.. just don't call it "The Integrated Release".'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-10-21 06:41:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Add definition of the Integrated Release

Remove the incubation and integration process and policies as a separate
file, replacing it with a single list of policies that integrated projects
are expected to follow.

Provide an explicit description of the new Integrated Release, based on
co-dependent gating and trust rules.

Change-Id: Ie2bba43dfd7faddab7afe6b3c54261fd2c0463ed

commit_message:
Fixes aggressive use of translation hints

The oslo.i18n docs say not to use the hints if the message will
ultimately be user facing:
    http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html

Change-Id: I7162bcb3dd23f5df2f1220ec531b2e40b2588ce2

commit_message:
Update barbican client usage

1. Update the code of creating a barbican client
due to its recent change.

2. Make the barbican_disabled defaults to True as
the two barbican patches below are not
merged yet, which breaks solum gate.

  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/127313
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/127865

3. Fix bugs for using shelve as the default key store.

Change-Id: Id5d8e125373b7dae91293bd36c46d5a5cc3a4d2b

So I like this idea. I like it so much that I implemented it already as an external project:

https://github.com/mtreinish/subunit2sql

which I've also already put on pypi.

I'm in the process of moving this over to stackforge too. Which will make contributions easier. 

I don't want to make it an official QA project though. It's not something I view as OpenStack specific.and should live as an external library. We can easily use it to build OpenStack specific tooling which would be a better suited part of the QA program.

The only thing subunit2sql is missing from this proposal is a rest api, but I don't think we actually need that. Just having a DB api is sufficient if a rest api is needed for something it's a simple matter to build that up around the DB layer.

So I think if you're planning on doing work on this it would be better to contribute to subunit2sql instead."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-09 19:48:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

I believe we need to "let in" lots of code and lots of teams of people who produce such code into the big tent of OpenStack, without burgeoning the Integrated Release by cogating all of that, or requiring the horizontal-scaling-efforts (docs, qa, etc) to take responsibility for them, and also without indicating (whether explicitly or implicitly) that those teams are The One True Way within our community to do the thing they do.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-10-09 19:10:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Doug: I guess my point here is that all "OpenStack project teams" are "official". IMHO there should be no intermediary area where you are an unofficial OpenStack project team. You can be out of the big tent (in stackforge), or in the big tent (under oversight of the TC, in openstack/* namespace, if you meet the "new team requirements").

So I don't think there is a need for a separate document (in addition to the charter mentioning project teams and the new-team-requirements doc)'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-27 18:01:17.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

I created a separate patch containing all of the changes from this series so I am abandoning the old series.'}]

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-03 09:02:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-10-03 09:56:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I think the "coordinated release cycle" must be "development milestones + time-based release at the end". Saying "projects following the Coordinated Release Cycle prepare a final release at the end of each cycle" tends to acknowledge that if you do a final release at the end (in addition to intermediary releases) this is still "coordinated release cycle". I think that if you do your own thing during the cycle and you try to push a final around the same date as the coordinated release cycle final release, then you're doing some imitation of the coordinated release cycle, not the coordinated release cycle. Libraries can be special-cased within the "coordinated release cycle" so that they still belong in it.

So it might be worth calling "compatible release cycle" a release schedule where you try to align with the final release only, and call it out explicitly here. You'd end up with 4 categories:

- projects which do coordinated release cycle *and* are managed to RelMgt team (think Nova today)
- projects which follow coordinated release cycle but are directly managed by team members (think Manila today)
- projects which do a "compatible release cycle" (think Swift today)
- projects that do their own thing or a rolling release (think TripleO today)'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-10-03 10:50:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-03 14:05:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

Thierry, I was struggling to balance listing all of the variations and describing the ones we wanted teams to follow and combine those with rules elsewhere. If we only want the rules to apply to the set of projects managed by the release team, maybe we should focus on that aspect and not bother to list the other variations? I'd love to have you take a stab at more detailed wording in a comment or etherpad or something that would be easy to fold into the patch when I prepare the next set of updates (I don't want to disrupt the conversation by doing that every time someone proposes a small change)."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-10-03 16:48:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Comments or questions throughout.'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2014-10-20 23:30:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I'm generally on board with where this is going, but I'd like to consider this aspect a bit more.

I think that a benefit of the big-tent program is making it easier for projects to be part of the broader OpenStack effort without the end goal being to join the "core" openstack group of projects.  In my mind, that blurs the line between "stackforge" and "openstack" to the point where it is no longer useful (if it's even useful now).

To that end, I think we should consider eliminating the stackforge project prefix.  It is currently a signal as to whether something is or is not a component of openstack.  We should instead consider it a place to put the work that the openstack community is working on, and to that end, move almost everything in stackforge to openstack.  The signalling for how projects relate to each other, which are required, and their level of production-readiness are made elsewhere (rather than in their names!).

I would love to get rid of the 'sorting hat' thing we do with every new project, reduce the barrier to entry (and migration toward "core"), and get us out of the business of renaming projects because their administrative status has changed.

Logistically, that requires some alterations to this change, and changes further down the stack related to signalling project maturity, etc.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-21 20:01:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(7 comments)

@Jim - I think I like the idea of removing stackforge, but since some of us still want the TC to maintain *some* control over projects we should probably do that separately from the rest of this discussion. Some projects may prefer not to submit to any of the oversight at all, so it may still be useful to have a separate namespace for them.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-10-24 12:44:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Jim: I think openstack/* should be for OpenStack projects, which at the very minimum should be vaguely aligned to the OpenStack mission, and following the OpenStack way (at least the 4 opens). So while most stackforge projects would probably fit the bill, I expect there would be a few which would not fit, given the total absence of checks on stackforge today. If you move most of stackforge/* to openstack/*, should we keep stackforge for projects that have nothing to do with openstack or do not want to align with the OpenStack way ? (I'd say "no")

There is also the question of name checks. Some people consider that things in a openstack/ repo are OpenStack things, so naming violations (or other rights violations) engage the Foundation and its members. That is why currently anything entering openstack/* is subject to a costly and lengthy name check. In order for the "everything in openstack" plan to be doable, we would have to relax this rule (and replace with a cursory check combined with a "rename if challenged" action).

Would you also move all of openstack-infra/* to openstack/* ? If not, why not ?'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-27 18:00:50.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

I created a separate patch containing all of the changes from this series so I am abandoning the old series.'}]

No this isn't going to change the world, but it gets rid of some confusing terminology that gave people the impression that programs were much more heavyweight than projects, which is completely backwards."}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-10-20 12:40:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Not sure I can vote in series, but commenting on each with my potential concerns or places to think more.'}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2014-10-21 05:52:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I am not sure I agree with the underlying premise here.

Sure, I can see that we want to allow competing implementations and let the best one win. I can even see that one day we might agree as a community to experiment with a replacement to something like nova. However, I'd expect to see that experimentation happen within the context of the compute program, not as an entirely separate thing.

In my mind this is what has concerned me about the deployment program for the last release or so -- we haven't been exploring other options as a community, we've picked a winner and gone with it. However, that's not a failure in programs, its our failure for excluding those other communities from that program. There is clear value in a Deployment program. There's also clear value in the work we know as "tripleo". However, there is also value in the other forms of deployment that our community use, and they should be included in that program.

Programs should be groupings of subject matter experts. There is still value in that.'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-10-21 07:31:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Comments inline.

@Jay, @Doug, I agree - this retains the powers of the TC as an oversight body for deciding what (and who) is in/out. And I'm OK with that in and of itself. I think we should significantly change the basis by which the TC decides that -- and the following patches go into more detail on that, so I won't say more about it here.

@Michael, I wrote a long reply then deleted it. I don't agree with your assertion that experimentation must happen within a given project; it certainly can, but I don't think it has to. We've had some successes and some failures on both sides of that. I also don't think I agree with your assertions about the deployment program, but I haven't been able to articulate it so I'm going to come back to that another time."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-10-21 07:50:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm with Jay here - I don't think this changes anything - the issue isn't terminology, its structural, and if you don't change the structure, you don't change the issue. TripleO already has within it multiple implementations (ansible + heat, heat deployments + heat, and docker), moreso I dare say than any other program than oslo in terms of competing implementations.

Honestly though, I don't particularly care what its called: as long as 'TC decides whats in OpenStack' exists anywhere, the pressure to be official will exist, whether its project / progam/ team / SIG..."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-21 19:44:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

@Michael - Yes, I'd like to think we could have programs continue to support competing implementations. Apparently we have real cases where that is not true, though, for a variety of reasons.

@lifeless - As Devananda said, some of the other changes later in the series make the structural changes a bit more apparent, especially with respect to the criteria for becoming an "official team".'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-10-27 18:00:42.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

I created a separate patch containing all of the changes from this series so I am abandoning the old series.'}]

commit_message:
Blueprint for Websockify security proxy framework

This blueprint proposes a generic framework for supporting
man-in-the-middle authentication and encryption between
Websockify and the hypervisor graphics servers.  It also
proposes a reference driver for that framework for TLS
security.

Spec for blueprint websocket-proxy-to-host-security

Change-Id: I23c5a43788afcb705b0d879cf5df4b49f0aa7a67
Previously-approved: juno

commit_message:
Check for existence of screen before start/stop

Running devstack in the devstack gate environment doesn't
create a screen for the running services. This causes the start,
and stop screen functions in redstack to fail. Fix this by only
performing the start and stop functions if a screen exists.

Partial-bug: 1386337
Change-Id: I2a87e7409575d1000286a7a3742d29a9cc877a8e

commit_message:
Cleanup of tenant network tests

Moves tenant network tests out of test_network.py
into test_tenant_networks.py which already has
tenant network tests and merges the test classes

Port floating_ips_bulk extention to v2.1

commit_message:
Compute: Catch binding failed exception while init host

While compute starts it will init all instances,
if an exception is raised from one instance
(e.g NovaException during plug_vifs),
then the compute process exits unexpectedly
because of this unhandled exception.
The commit catches the NovaException during
plug_vifs and set instance to error state,
then the compute process can be started normally
even if this exception is raised.

Closes-bug: #1324041

Change-Id: I899fa4947370d7d94fe2b82c71959dea335d8b60

@Dan, the issue with showing 'phyp' for the powervc driver (powervm images in this case) is more or less usability at this point, i.e. Horizon shows the hypervisor_type from the images and it's confusing that it shows phyp when it's not really phyp that is being used (libvirt isn't used, the powervc driver is).

If that doesn't work, then I'd probably propose this alternative to give time to do the image metadata migration in the powervc driver:

"Add temporary workaround to the hvtype.canonicalize() method to re-write it, as we did for Xen (to be removed after a release - basically gives users a 1 release window to update their image properties)."'}, {'account_id': 8574, 'date': '2014-10-21 14:44:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Is this 'powervm' for PowerVC driver? https://github.com/stackforge/powervc-driver

The image for 'phyp' may be a little different from the image for PowerVC driver, so that we need another constant value to distinguish them."}, {'account_id': 9493, 'date': '2014-10-21 14:46:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

it's significantly simplifying the work for the stackforge's powervc driver"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-10-21 14:55:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

> it's confusing that it shows phyp when it's not really phyp 
> that is being used (libvirt isn't used, the powervc driver > is).

This is mis-interpreting what the hypervisor type value is representing. It is explicitly about what *hypervisor* is used, not about what management layer is on top of the hypervisor.ie what is the machine ABI that guest images must satisfy in order to boot. For both of the mgmt layers / drivers you refer to, the underlying hypervisor is still the same, so we should have only 1 constant defined for this.

If we need to put a short term hack in the canonicalize method to translate the old data, as we did for Xen, that's ok with me. It would only live for 1 release cycle, so given that we're in Kilo, we'd remove the canonicalization workaround in Lmmmm release."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-21 22:48:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

commit_message:
Translate 'powervm' hypervisor_type to 'phyp' for scheduling

This adds a temporary translation of the 'powervm' hypervisor type
image metadata to 'phyp' for scheduling.

The powervc-driver in stackforge uses the hypervisor type of 'powervm'
for scheduling so this is needed to make that work until the driver
can get a translation shim in place to convert powervm to phyp in
image metadata.

Closes-Bug: #1370613

Change-Id: I4b20ffcb9911806db821f2902e09248dfa89d845

commit_message:
Give a reason why NoValidHost in select_destinations

When we can't schedule an instance build because there are fewer
available hosts than requested number of instances we raise NoValidHost
but don't give a reason.

This change adds a reason and a unit test for the greater-than-zero
NoValidHost case.

Related-Bug: #1372588

Change-Id: Ibd17b3d582b6e1470cd075d73e3dcaa63c9a667e

Sync middleware from oslo-incubator

Returning this outdated code allows grenade jobs not to fall
In all other cases to fix this bug we should have this outdated
code in nova

commit_message:
Revert "Replace outdated oslo-incubator middleware"

This is breaking the Juno -> master grenade path. As we are using the old
api-paste.ini file which requires the oslo-incubator copy of request_id

This breakage didn't happen from Icehouse -> master since the icehouse
api-paste.ini didn't have request_id as a middleware. request_id is only
used as middleware in the V21/V3 API and not the V2 API.

Closes-Bug: #1383757
This reverts commit 641de5666f38532252e91735a1cd2611d96c489a.

Change-Id: I1ca6bddf9d9370529e999efcc7eae60622e19e6f

commit_message:
Set logging level for glanceclient to WARN

When capturing a snapshot for example, glanceclient logs
the whole uploaded image into the nova compute logs as
glanceclient's log level is set to DEBUG by default

Change-Id: Ie764517c2a4b91cb02c15096f7f0b4138900c92d

commit_message:
Nova should be in charge of its log defaults

Oslo's log module has a set_defaults which Nova can use
to set the context logging format and default log levels.
We should not have to fix default levels in oslo and then
sync across to Nova. This becomes all the more important
when we move to oslo.log library so we should get started
now

Change-Id: Id47099d5a755bc2923b05fe4bef270a7c0f99389

commit_message:
Reduce the complexity of _get_guest_config()

Running flake8 to check for cyclomatic complexity showed that the
libvirt driver's _get_guest_config() method was the worst offender,
with a complexity of 67. This commit simply refactors this method,
splitting off nested cases into their own methods, and reduces the
complextity to 40. No functional changes are included.

Change-Id: Ic27e091f922118edb48b233fb31c702d9528bb75

commit_message:
VMware: Remove redundant fake.reset() in test_vm_util

We fake.reset() in setUp(), so no need to do it in tearDown() too.

TrivialFix

This is really a distro bug in their libvirt/xen packaging. It is expected that the default path used by libvirt should "Just work". Per your commit message debian has broken the default setup by using a different path. They should either change the install location or patch libvirt to point to the correct place. I don't think OpenStack should be trying to workaround such obvious distro packager bugs. We have an expectation that libvirt defaults should "just work" and only need to override them if wanting to experiment with different binaries'}, {'account_id': 91, 'date': '2014-10-01 11:28:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi Dan, thanks for your comments.

I agree with the packaging stuff, but there are other issues here:

1. As per [*] I understand that the libvirt XML expects a bootloader. Currently OpenStack generated libvirt.xml file lacks it, but if it is expected we should generate it.

2. libvirt is setting the bootloader to a full path "/usr/bin/pygrub", but this is deprecated [**], the warning below is shown in the logs. IMHO this should be solved in libvirt [***], because of the deprecation warning.
  
    libxl: warning: libxl_bootloader.c:413:bootloader_disk_attached_cb: bootloader='/usr/bin/pygrub' is deprecated; use bootloader='pygrub' instead

3. pygrub, that is the default bootloader, does not support Qcow2 disks. pvgrub does, but it is not possible to tell libvirt to use it (via OpenStack or via some libvirt config). Even if I would be able to force configure Xen to use pvgrub, libvirt will overwrite it to "/usr/bin/pygrub".

Currently we are stuck using the depreacted xend because of this (2). I
could file a bug to Debian and Ubuntu saying that they should install pygrub in
its standard location, but this just solves (2), but no (3). For instance we want
to start working on the testing of the CoW support using Xen+libvirt, but we
cannot start because of this.

How could I as an operator tell that I want to use pvgrub instead of pygrub, if
I am not able to specify this in libvirt or OpenStack?

[*] https://www.redhat.com/archives/libvir-list/2014-August/msg00804.html
[**] http://wiki.xen.org/wiki/PyGrub
[***] https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1104695'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-01 12:24:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Is there any reason to ever use 'pygrub' instead of 'pvgrub', given that the latter has more features. 

It isn't nice to be in a situation where you can set the libvirt type for nova.conf to 'xen' but then have a broken deployment unless you also set a 'bootloader' arg. So rather than use a config parameter, it would nice if Nova would explicitly just "do the right thing" and configure "pvgrub" without having to be asked, so that qcow2 images work out of the box.'}, {'account_id': 91, 'date': '2014-10-01 12:40:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Workflow-1

Nice point. I agree with you with the fact that if pvgrub is available, pvgrub should (or must) be used. I will try to work something out and resubmit.

However, it is still possible that pygrub will be used (when pvgrub is not available). Then, regarding the point (2) from my previous comment, it will fail in Ubuntu/Debian. Right now there are three options to try to fix this: 1) have it fixed in libvirt, so that Xen does the magic (i.e. without setting the bootloader to a path as this is a deprecated option according to the logs and the Xen wiki); 2) have it fixed in Debian/Ubuntu, so they don't install pygrub in a weird location (or they patch libvirt to support that location); and 3) let nova do the magic. I would say that I am completely against 3, and that 1 and 2 are not mutually exclusive, but they're out of the scope here.

Would it fit to you if I refactor this change to support pvgrub?"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-10-01 12:43:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

If we can just make Nova do the right thing and configure pvgrub, falling back to configuring pygrub, that would be best.'}, {'account_id': 91, 'date': '2014-10-01 12:52:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Ok, thanks, I will work on it.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-07 16:27:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
libvirt: add xen bootloader discovery

Using libvirt + xen, when an instance is created without a kernel, a
bootloader should be provided. Currently OpenStack does not set it,
theferore the libvirt XML file does not contain this tag. in these
cases, libvirt will set a default bootloader, thay may or may not exist
on the system.

Xen supports two bootloaders: 'pvgrub' and 'pygrub'. Normally they are
installed in '/usr/bin/' but in some distributions such as Ubuntu and
Debian they are installed under '/usr/libexec/xen-MAJOR.MINOR/bin'.

This change tries to get the best available bootloader in the host, so
that no further configuration is needed by the operator, i.e. if they
set [libvirt]/virt_type=xen they do not need to configure the
bootloader, but nova will choose the best available option.

Change-Id: I9b5ab2f9d54c73b013c2eacce79e55f5f8b986e5

commit_message:
Provider Segment Support for Cisco Nexus Switches

This spec describes the work being done by the blueprint
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/ \
ml2-cisco-nexus-mechdriver-providernet
which implements ML2 provider segment support
for the Cisco 3K, 5K and 7K Nexus switches.

Change-Id: I733b007f629e601101ba2938fecc734deef7d5a6

The bug is caused by consecutive client calls when
fetching users' roles in a project.

The fix was to use the /v3/role_assignments endpoint.
Which retrieves all roles in a single client call
(dashboards/admin/projects/workflows.py:
UpdateProjectGroupsAction and UpdateProjectUsersAction).

The compatibility to the previous keystoneclient version
is maintained.

In a scenario with 1000 users with a role in a project
(using devstack), the time to render the Modify Users
page dropped from 45s to 2.5s

commit_message:
Fixes bad performance when editing project members

The bug is caused by consecutive client calls when
fetching users' roles in a project.

The fix was to use the /v3/role_assignments endpoint.
Which retrieves all roles in a single client call
(dashboards/admin/projects/workflows.py:
UpdateProjectGroupsAction and UpdateProjectUsersAction).

The compatibility to the previous keystoneclient version
is maintained.

In a scenario with 1000 users with a role in a project
(using devstack), the time to render the Modify Users
page dropped from 45s to 2.5s

Conflicts:
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/projects/tests.py

NOTE(jpomero): The conflict is because of a signature change
to one of the project test methods.

Change-Id: Ic72ebea0db226faf98c5e04d00d76dedd1fb01c1
Closes-bug: #1278920
(cherry picked from commit ed43be0a0f40c4b065472da27e6ef6e59a6789ca)

This is a fix for the issues encountered when a service is not
configured or a service endpoint is not reachable. This fix
will add tolerance for these errors so that an error message is
displayed but the dashboard page will still load, not an error page.
This makes it easier for the user to recover by allowing them to
go to a different page, select a different region, or logout. This

image service endpoint, or when a single endpoint is not reachable
for whatever reason.

image services so that the dashboard will not display them if
the service is not configured.

catalog so that not all services are available in all regions, or
some of the service endpoints are not reachable.

commit_message:
Tolerate service catalog and endpoint connection errors

This is a fix for the issues encountered when a service is not
configured or a service endpoint is not reachable. This fix
will add tolerance for these errors so that an error message is
displayed but the dashboard page will still load, not an error page.
This makes it easier for the user to recover by allowing them to
go to a different page, select a different region, or logout. This
makes sense in many cases such as when a region only contains an
image service endpoint, or when a single endpoint is not reachable
for whatever reason.

It also adds permissions to the panels that require compute or
image services so that the dashboard will not display them if
the service is not configured.

To test these changes you will need to set up your keystone service
catalog so that not all services are available in all regions, or
some of the service endpoints are not reachable.

Change-Id: Ie04699d1fb1d4db13a7f4dcf1bdfd23bf21aab80
Closes-Bug: 1323811
Closes-Bug: 1207636
(cherry picked from commit 407c17b38a05580ea2117e215efa86c541b584f6)

commit_message:
Preserve services region when switching projects

This fixes the issue where the services region might be changed
when switching projects. The new user object will get the same
services region that was being used previously.

Closes-Bug: #1357047
Change-Id: Iefcc8acf482e2ccbcd8cce202a417e5a0a587399

commit_message:
Change use_swift test from or to and

the test to determine if $use_swift is set in cluster_ha is:

  !($storage_hash['images_ceph'] and $storage_hash['objects_ceph'])
    or !$storage_hash['images_vcenter']

this prevents the proper setting of $use_swift causing duplicate
 keys when ceph should be used instead of swift. See bug for matrix
 of results

Change-Id: I6c22b0d1a95eb47bdde5946020823de2c86c64ca
Closes-bug: #1383315

Neutron is not Ironic

The element to install OpenStack clients has a thinko using Ironic's
virtualenv and install options for the Neutron client.

commit_message:
Limit python26 jobs to icehouse/juno for server projects

For server projects in the openstack namespace, limit the python26 jobs
to icehouse/juno branches only.

Change-Id: Ib495467e00e4b6abf2b3c2b9445b51652ba25167
Co-Authored-By: Michael Krotscheck<krotscheck@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Link to local copy of cliff and stevedore docs

We used to host documentation for cliff and stevedore on
readthedocs.org, but have updated the publishing jobs so that the docs
are hosted on docs.openstack.org with the other projects. This change
updates the links to the documentation on the main page listing all of
the projects.

Change-Id: Ibe5f01c6fee57353fcd8cd187e6894247ff88a56

commit_message:
Revert Neutron upstream sync patches

Due to unstable patches merged w/o CI +1,
accept the following commits:

* Revert "TEMPORARY neutron-keystone fix"
  This reverts commit cf39a7503c5a6006ed7a4f2b46b2ef43d7d4dda8.
* Revert "Neutron HA composition model"
  This reverts commit 0badbc4e23831a20938a1bca2719557dd8704ae0.
* Revert "Adapt upstream puppet-neutron into fuel"
  This reverts commit 55477e2c4abac14c8a2e8e06a2d7d0f26740665f.
* Revert "Sync with upstream puppet-neutron"
  This reverts commit 247ea68f27a9cb515c82ff8d23b50ee440f956fe.
* Revert "Purge old neutron manifests and move our customized files"
  This reverts commit 35e55b82b2c74f2cb2998f39a5bb3ad67a40818c.

Change-Id: Iad04de4e83a6fb78a9e5cda2f196e1cd3aea14e4

An auth_host with : in the name is going to require wrapping in []
because otherwise the : is confused with the port separator, so the
code doesn't have to verify that it's an IPv6 address. This allows

commit_message:
Remove netaddr package requirement

An auth_host with : in the name is going to require wrapping in []
because otherwise the : is confused with the port separator, so the
code doesn't have to verify that it's an IPv6 address. This allows
the removal of the netaddr package requirement.

Change-Id: I0d4c622b360769f1a7587d3c230e50d22f5b75a4

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
remove rtfd docs jobs for cliff and stevedore

After we have the docs for cliff and stevedore fully hosted on
docs.openstack.org we can remove these jobs.

This changes how v1 works. Now when you get an SRV record using the v1 api, the priority field is displayed as null. Instead it is displayed as part of the data field. In the records table, the priority is actually a separate column which is no longer getting populated. That's why it was originally done as separate 'get' and 'set', but the functionality of those looks like they've been changed over time.

So, if v1 has to stay the same, a different way needs to be found to fix this."}, {'account_id': 395, 'date': '2014-10-27 16:24:31.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-26 22:14:04.000000000', 'message': 'Don't do set / get priority for SRV records

This would take the "head" and set the priority to it. This is actually bad for
SRV since it would be the weight and not the priority that would be set to
priority. Also it breaks the record.

Change-Id: I9d6d00e4e336267dc6b229b5eeedbd6d12629303
'}]
commit_message:
Don't do set / get priority for SRV records

This would take the "head" and set the priority to it. This is actually bad for
SRV since it would be the weight and not the priority that would be set to
priority. Also it breaks the record.

Change-Id: I9d6d00e4e336267dc6b229b5eeedbd6d12629303

commit_message:
Restore process fails managing big data stream from swift

Currently Freezer has a bug in tar_restore() and
object_to_stream() functions, as the remote chunks needs
to be set to a far smaller value to keep the connection
stream working during restore tasks.

Also the way how the end of data stream is implemented now
is not efficient for big data streams, as it should be managed
adding False or None in the Pipe and properly managed in
the other side of the pipe.

The default segments size is now set to 64MB from 128MB.
This can be more appropriate for low resources nodes.

Change-Id: I00c4cc984e90ea1368b8842cd112a35085e14b11
LAUNCHPAD: https://bugs.launchpad.net/freezer/+bug/1384795

commit_message:
Big Switch: Switch to TLSv1 in server manager

Switch to TLSv1 for the connections to the backend
controllers. The default SSLv3 is no longer considered
secure.

TLSv1 was chosen over .1 or .2 because the .1 and .2 weren't
added until python 2.7.9 so TLSv1 is the only compatible option
for py26.

Closes-Bug: #1384487
Change-Id: I68bd72fc4d90a102003d9ce48c47a4a6a3dd6e03
(cherry picked from commit 62588957fbeccfb4f80eaa72bef2b86b6f08dcf8)

I found this digging through giant stacktraces generated by using the following patch with line 344 uncommented. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/128588/4/neutron/service.py

By getting a stacktrace at each eventlet yield, I could find the last coroutine that yielded right before the one that hit a deadlock. In this case, it was always a delete_port routine hitting its post-commit methods which try to send RPC messages. This normally wouldn't be a problem, except these were triggered by L3 methods that still had open transactions, which blocked new locks on the DB."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-10-16 15:27:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

If I understand this correctly, we have methods wrapped in a DB transaction in _update_router_db that end up making RPC calls in delete_port (this is even more true for DVR where more than one RPC call is made). So your change in [1] was not going deep enough as we still have the outer transaction (in _update_router_db) that wraps the RPC call made in delete_port (that's been moved out of the inner transaction block in change [1]). 

I am a little wary of the change you propose here as it alters the behavior quite drastically, and for all the plugins that use the l3_db base class. Who knows what the side-effects are going to be. The ultimate fix would be to eradicate this all DB/RPC altogether by stopping sending actual RPC messages when we notify. What we could do instead is to put messages into an in-memory queue that gets served by a looping call that does the actual RPC messages. Would that be our panacea?

[1] - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/127943/"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-10-16 16:18:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The other idea I have been mulling over, and that has come up in the past when looking at these types of issues, is that we should really start using observer patterns when dealing with status changes. 

Hijacking the code flow whenever we need something to know about something else is simply mental! In the ML2 plugin this happens every time there is an "if l3plugin: do this" for example, and this is the source of the grief we experience.

During Kilo I'd like to tackle this with a more profound approach, and this means that a patch like this one might turn out to be unnecessary. The question now is: can it be seen as a sensible stop-gap? I would think so, but in this particular case, the change made looks pretty scary.'}, {'account_id': 7016, 'date': '2014-10-16 18:21:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Kevin I will check this patch and will update my comments.'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2014-10-16 19:15:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This change doesn't look nearly as scary as it seems. All of these are just starting transactions and calling something else before they do anything with them. So calling something else before starting the transaction isn't losing any rollback expectations."}, {'account_id': 10370, 'date': '2014-10-16 20:43:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2014-10-16 21:07:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Sorry, forgot to respond to your other comments.

An RPC queue isn't good enough because we need to capture the entire post-commit operations of ML2 drivers, which could include HTTP requests or carrier pigeons.

I really like the refactor to cleanly separate L2 from L3 (and other services) and would love to work on that. However, I think we should move forward with this patch because we need a fix back-portable to Juno."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-10-17 01:13:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> This change doesn't look nearly as scary as it seems. All of these are just starting transactions and calling something else before they do anything with them. So calling something else before starting the transaction isn't losing any rollback expectations.

I am not sure I understand what you're saying, to be perfectly honest, I'd need to look into this. Bear with me."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-10-17 01:21:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> An RPC queue isn't good enough because we need to capture the entire post-commit operations of ML2 drivers, which could include HTTP requests or carrier pigeons.

Perhaps this is not worth it in light of the effort below.

> I really like the refactor to cleanly separate L2 from L3 (and other services) and would love to work on that. 

Great, I'd love to discuss this with you in great details at the Summit, but I'd like to get started sooner, I'll put a quick spec together in the next couple of days.

> However, I think we should move forward with this patch because we need a fix back-portable to Juno.

I would kindly disagree. DVR is experimental for Juno, so we don't *need* a back-portable fix if we are unable to find the right one. We may have to account for the fact that its initial implementation had some weaknesses that are being addressed in Kilo. This is the timeframe where we assess if the functionality becomes more robust and feature rich, and perhaps ready to take over legacy routers as the default option for Neutron routing."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2014-10-17 01:57:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Regardless of back-porting it, I think we should move forward with this patch. I don't see any reason that these should be starting a transaction and then calling another method before doing anything. There is nothing to rollback if an exception is thrown."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2014-10-17 04:15:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-17 05:25:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

[{'created': '2014-10-16 09:02:33.000000000', 'message': "_update_router_db: don't hold open transactions

The router update db methods start transactions and call
their super methods with the transactions held open.
This becomes a problem when the update results in an
interface removal that results in a port table lock.
Because they are still holding open a transaction,
other sessions are blocked from getting an SQL lock
on the same tables while the delete_port operation
starts performing RPC notifications, external controller,
calls, etc.

During those external calls, eventlet will yield and
another thread may try to get a lock on the port table,
causing a deadlock.

Closes-Bug: #1377241
Change-Id: I5fdb6b24bf2fb80ac5e36a742aa7056db72c8c7d
"}, {'created': '2014-10-17 04:15:41.000000000', 'message': "_update_router_db: don't hold open transactions

This patch prevents the L3 methods from starting a transaction
before calling the interface removal functions. Now that the
port removal will happen outside of the L3 transaction, a
failure to update the router DB information will not rollback
the port deletion operation.

===Details===

The router update db methods start transactions and call
their super methods with the transactions held open.
This becomes a problem when the update results in an
interface removal which uses a port table lock.

Because the delete_port caller is still holding open a
transaction, other sessions are blocked from getting an
SQL lock on the same tables when delete_port starts
performing RPC notifications, external controller,
calls, etc. During those external calls, eventlet will
yield and another thread may try to get a lock on the
port table, causing the infamous mysql/eventlet deadlock.

This separation of L2/L3 transactions is similiar to change
I3ae7bb269df9b9dcef94f48f13f1bde1e4106a80 in nature. Even
though there is a loss in the atomic behavior of the interface
removal operation, it was arguably incorrect to begin with.
The restoration of port DB records during a rollback after some
other failure doesn't undo the backend operations (e.g. REST calls)
that happened during the original deletion. So, having a delete
rollback without corresponding 'create_port' calls to the backend
causes a loss in consistency.

Closes-Bug: #1377241
Change-Id: I5fdb6b24bf2fb80ac5e36a742aa7056db72c8c7d

commit_message:
_update_router_db: don't hold open transactions

This patch prevents the L3 _update_router_db method from
starting a transaction before calling the gateway interface
removal functions. With these port changes now occuring
outside of the L3 DB transaction, a failure to update the
router DB information will not rollback the port deletion
operation.

The 'VPN in use' check had to be moved inside of the DB deletion
transaction now that there isn't an enclosing transaction to undo
the delete when an 'in use' error is raised.

===Details===

The router update db method starts a transaction and calls
the gateway update method with the transaction held open.
This becomes a problem when the update results in an
interface removal which uses a port table lock.

Because the delete_port caller is still holding open a
transaction, other sessions are blocked from getting an
SQL lock on the same tables when delete_port starts
performing RPC notifications, external controller calls,
etc. During those external calls, eventlet will
yield and another thread may try to get a lock on the
port table, causing the infamous mysql/eventlet deadlock.

This separation of L2/L3 transactions is similiar to change
I3ae7bb269df9b9dcef94f48f13f1bde1e4106a80 in nature. Even
though there is a loss in the atomic behavior of the interface
removal operation, it was arguably incorrect to begin with.
The restoration of port DB records during a rollback after some
other failure doesn't undo the backend operations (e.g. REST calls)
that happened during the original deletion. So, having a delete
rollback without corresponding 'create_port' calls to the backend
causes a loss in consistency.

Closes-Bug: #1377241
Change-Id: I5fdb6b24bf2fb80ac5e36a742aa7056db72c8c7d

commit_message:
Increase the default poll duration for Cisco n1kv

Increase the poll duration for Cisco N1Kv, from 10s to 60s and also
clean up the /etc/neutron/plugins/cisco/cisco_plugins.ini file. The
current poll duration of 10s causes that VSM to unnecessarily taking
frequent CPU cycles, resulting in the failure of other tasks in scale
configurations.

Closes-Bug: 1357030
(cherry picked from commit 6e08e477a9cb46b1d371c2c9812e5ce9f4cf69be)

Conflicts:
	etc/neutron/plugins/cisco/cisco_plugins.ini
	neutron/plugins/cisco/common/config.py

Change-Id: I95747f35bae5b7157391c1698c0fe84d2126aa10

commit_message:
Big Switch: Switch to TLSv1 in server manager

Switch to TLSv1 for the connections to the backend
controllers. The default SSLv3 is no longer considered
secure.

TLSv1 was chosen over .1 or .2 because the .1 and .2 weren't
added until python 2.7.9 so TLSv1 is the only compatible option
for py26.

Conflicts:

	neutron/tests/unit/bigswitch/test_servermanager.py
    Unit test changes couldn't be back-ported because they don't
    exist in Icehouse.

Closes-Bug: #1384487
Change-Id: I68bd72fc4d90a102003d9ce48c47a4a6a3dd6e03
(cherry picked from commit 62588957fbeccfb4f80eaa72bef2b86b6f08dcf8)

commit_message:
Fix a recent ipv6 UT regression

This fixes UT failures on systems without the procfs entry
by adding appropriate mocking.  The problem introduced by
the following change:
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116826/
    commit 0c963f6140237d8d3f361c6aaa7d2a6b656504db

Also, add a test for the case which the change in question fixed.

Closes-Bug: #1363805
Related-Bug: #1361542
Change-Id: I72842c3446f3275e2288adc411540ab036025ed0
(cherry picked from commit 6f5f14872387f3814d3c421f07e68f6ce45f7d7d)

commit_message:
Remove unused py33 tox env

It's apparent that Neutron is not expected to gain Py3K support on
its stable/icehouse branch, and so developers are not expected to
run the py33 tox env.

Change-Id: Ieae7819e0489ae19b7fcfb63497e06527c918b5c

(2 comments)

@Joe, do we need a bug for this? Admitted we are not familiar with the Nova process.

To make a long history short, the original goal was two-fold

1. enable Keystoen V3 support for novaclient
2. integrate with keystoneclient so common functionality such as authentication, (http) session management, catalog parsing, etc are provided from a single source

Basically 1 is the side effect of 2.

Jamie Lennox's patch, which was merged awhile back, implemented 2 for Nova client library. Now David's trying to finish up the second part, which is the CLI piece.

However, there's small gap between what keystoneclient session and Nova HTTP session, which is to key track of timing for each API call. David's just trying to bridge that gap, as the side effect of his CLI patch.

He's being asked to split up his CLI patch. And here we are ...

If process is the only hold up, we'll be more than happy to file a bug and fix the commit message. But otherwise, are there anything else that is out of the ordinary?"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-10-16 18:36:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add --timings support when SessionClient is used

SessionClient has no --timings support, which is a regression
 for those who depend on it.  This patch adds the support to
 measure the duration of Keystone authentication and calls to
 SessionClient request.  Timing data when requested by user
 through CLI is presented per call and total time execution.

Change-Id: Ifd4685118a485b3dcefe12a20a7a3056bc583495

messages:
[{'account_id': 13587, 'date': '2014-10-27 15:09:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2014-10-27 15:09:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 13587, 'date': '2014-10-27 15:12:05.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

It was a test'}]

commit_message:
Move disabling of metadata and ipv6_ra to _destroy_router_namespace

I noticed that disable_ipv6_ra is called from the wrong place and that
in some cases it was called with a bogus router_id because the code
made an incorrect assumption about the context.  In other case, it was
never called because _destroy_router_namespace was being called
directly.  This patch moves the disabling of metadata and ipv6_ra in
to _destroy_router_namespace to ensure they get called correctly and
avoid duplication.

Change-Id: Ia76a5ff4200df072b60481f2ee49286b78ece6c4
Closes-Bug: #1383495

commit_message:
Sahara Cluster scaling benchmark

The benchmark allows to test Sahara Cluster up and down scaling
operations.

commit_message:
tox: ensure publish-docs directory always exists

In some cases (e.g., if only files in locale directories changed),
doctest.py does not create the publish-docs/training-guides directory
which is needed to publish the labs scripts.

With this patch, said directory is always created.

Change-Id: I9014b233c5b8cf5c0516fab9592f5aeed6d08d6c

commit_message:
Allow mysql running on an another host

When we have a DATABASE_HOST configured to something else than 127.0.0.1
we are pretty sure we don't want to have a remote host for accessing the
database.

Change-Id: I8eb51ac2a8feb567c3572adb76e268a57ad8e76a

The order itself may need some tweaking, but I don't recollect any association calls because we do not support any M:N relationships."}, {'account_id': 13375, 'date': '2014-10-20 23:15:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I think this will make the user feel uncomfortable because he/she created so many parallel resources but has to get to know weather the resources has been referred by each other.'}, {'account_id': 13375, 'date': '2014-10-20 23:19:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Plugin/DB additions for version 2 of LBaaS API

Added alembic migrations, models, db methods and plugin methods.
Added DEFERRED status for entities not linked to a load balancer.
Added to_dict method in BaseNeutron model.
Sql Alchemy models in its own module.
Plugin database methods are accessed by composition through the plugin.
Added data models to convert sql alchemy models before passing to driver.

Partially-implements: blueprint lbaas-api-and-objmodel-improvement

Change-Id: Iaec2c2315ae54418b341eb31e6b3ff53b02ca9d7
Co-authored-by: Brandon Logan <brandon.logan@rackspace.com>
Co-authored-by: Vijayendra Bhamidipati <vbhamidipati@paypal.com>
Co-authored-by: Craig Tracey <Craig.Tracey@gmail.com>
Co-authored-by: Doug Wiegley <dougw@a10networks.com>

commit_message:
Simplify multinode setup

* Use the fixed addresses from /etc/nodepool
* Expect the firewall configured by the ready script
* Use .ssh/config settings instead of populate the known hosts files
* Remove orphaned functions

This change depends on:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/114840

Change-Id: If904b858e9406a2e772ae6bcf1450539c67c1588

commit_message:
Bring doc build up to standard

Move the requirements definitions and documentation files to the
standard places used by other OpenStack projects so our doc publishing
jobs will work.

Change-Id: Iea630d827976fe517afacf4e373b3a125efff9c9

commit_message:
Adapt postgres container to postgresql 9.3

Binary and config paths are dependent on postgresql package
version. Adapted postgres to work with newer versions, but
left older configurations available in case paths change
back to the previous format.

Change-Id: I33de52e1b285c83d704f42909e86e49111e24ca6
Partial-Bug: #1386118

commit_message:
Inrease tick interval

  Increase tick_interval from 0 to 1. This is a workaround for passing
  1) TestTaskManagers.test_deletion_three_offline_nodes_and_one_online
  2) TestTaskManagers.test_delete_offile_nodes_and_recover_them
  Please consider it as a hotfix. Additional investigation is being
  performed.

Change-Id: I5a13941fd4695ab84b342eb4c1587f97081d4803
Partial-Bug: #1384631

commit_message:
Volume host affinity based VM placement

Blueprint: volume-host-affinity-based-vm-placement

Cinder scheduler schedules volume creation on certain host based on
scheduler filters in case of multi-node setup. For local volume
backends like LVM, the volume resides locally on the host where
volume create was scheduled.

For clustered filesystems like IBM General Parallel File System
(GPFS) which provides features like FPO (File Placement Optimizer),
the volume create command will be run on that host and volume will
be created locally if FPO is enabled. FPO is designed for efficiency
in case of Hadoop and MapReduce workloads. IBM GPFS Volume Driver
can be used to configure backends that use FPO enabled GPFS storage
pools.

There can be various use cases that leverage the volume locality
information, irrespective of cinder backend being used, and
instantiate the VM closer to where the volume resides.

Change-Id: I08ed8aa348ec5a211192312079b164284e63e876

commit_message:
Add package install support for tuskar

Support installing from packages and source for the tuskar element. Adds
svc-map support for tuskar-api to support the service being named
differently between source and package installs.

Change-Id: I189748f91b17e398d15b91bd1bd6ce2f2de02a73

commit_message:
Add package install support for tuskar-ui

Support installing from packages and source for the tuskar-ui element.
The post-configure.d script is also updated to only use the virtualenv
for Horizon if the $HORIZON_VENV_DIR environment variable is defined.

Change-Id: If42ca22fb173df0b35155ce760b94c1c6f2f9d28

commit_message:
Use oslo_debug_helper and remove our own version

With the latest version of oslotest, we can now take advantage
of a common oslo_debug_helper script.
We can now remove our own homebrewed version, minor changes to
tox.ini were needed.

Change-Id: I907f7203aefedc9b33c3dfbfecc9793e273a4a8f

commit_message:
Bring doc build up to standard

Move the requirements definitions and documentation files to the
standard places used by other OpenStack projects so our doc publishing
jobs will work.

Remove the todo extension and all todo items from the documentation.

Change-Id: Iea630d827976fe517afacf4e373b3a125efff9c9

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Enable HDFS NameNode High Availability with HDP 2.0.6 plugin

Extend HDP 2.0.6 plugin to include the setup and configuration of the
HDFS NameNode High Availability after creating, configuring and starting
the cluster.

Change-Id: Ic66be5487d5aaa095cdc25b9918a89e3bccfd074

Both commit message and bug report do not provide adequate information as to why this is the right fix. The log trace posted does not even contain the DBDuplicateEntry trace, so I am a bit at loss here.'}, {'account_id': 6788, 'date': '2014-10-27 13:05:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Armando, you are right. I tested it again, this patch doesn't affect the bug in any way. Now that I look at the code with fresh eyes I wonder what I was thinking when I submitted it :/"}, {'account_id': 6788, 'date': '2014-10-27 13:14:57.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This patch doesn't solve the bug. To give more context, postgresql throws an error if select for update is applied when an outer join returns an empty row (this happens when there's no correspondence for that row in one of the 2 tables involved in the join). See "SELECT FOR UPDATE/SHARE cannot be applied to the nullable side of an outer join " http://www.postgresql.org/message-id/21634.1160151923@sss.pgh.pa.us
This is not the case here, since IPAvailabilityRange has allocation_pool_id as foreign key, so there's a 1 to 1 correspondence for every row'}]

commit_message:
Force inner join in IPAllocationPool model

Update IPAllocationPool model so that the relationship to
IpAvailabilityRange is explicitly forced to use an inner join.
PostgreSQL doesn't support 'SELECT FOR UPDATE' on outer
joined queries.

Change-Id: I078fb02378a27af371e5fc26720c80128432c90d
Partial-Bug: #1364085

commit_message:
Ensure that crontabs package is installed

Keystone container do not have crontabs package installed which
breaks 'cron' usage in puppet manifests.

Change-Id: Id4d9258d149acd046bb7c4c4002c766dae9e3c29
Closes-Bug: #1386098

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-27 08:46:09.000000000', 'message': 'Volume host affinity based VM placement

Blueprint: volume-host-affinity-based-vm-placement

Cinder scheduler schedules volume creation on certain host based on
scheduler filters in case of multi-node setup. For local volume
backends like LVM, the volume resides locally on the host where
volume create was scheduled.

For clustered filesystems like IBM General Parallel File System
(GPFS) which provides features like FPO (File Placement Optimizer),
the volume create command will be run on that host and volume will
be created locally if FPO is enabled. FPO is designed for efficiency
in case of Hadoop and MapReduce workloads. IBM GPFS Volume Driver
can be used to configure backends that use FPO enabled GPFS storage
pools.

There can be various use cases that leverage the volume locality
information, irrespective of cinder backend being used, and
instantiate the VM closer to where the volume resides.

Addressed following review comments-
- Wrapped long lines
- Removed trailing spaces
- Removed the dependency that boot volumes should be FPO enabled
- Added performance impact in "Performance Impact" section

Change-Id: I12f4729d559a7d89c451da0b1196af00b7b27dc6
'}]
commit_message:
Volume host affinity based VM placement

Blueprint: volume-host-affinity-based-vm-placement

Cinder scheduler schedules volume creation on certain host based on
scheduler filters in case of multi-node setup. For local volume
backends like LVM, the volume resides locally on the host where
volume create was scheduled.

For clustered filesystems like IBM General Parallel File System
(GPFS) which provides features like FPO (File Placement Optimizer),
the volume create command will be run on that host and volume will
be created locally if FPO is enabled. FPO is designed for efficiency
in case of Hadoop and MapReduce workloads. IBM GPFS Volume Driver
can be used to configure backends that use FPO enabled GPFS storage
pools.

There can be various use cases that leverage the volume locality
information, irrespective of cinder backend being used, and
instantiate the VM closer to where the volume resides.

Addressed following review comments-
- Wrapped long lines
- Removed trailing spaces
- Removed the dependency that boot volumes should be FPO enabled
- Added performance impact in "Performance Impact" section

Change-Id: I12f4729d559a7d89c451da0b1196af00b7b27dc6

commit_message:
Fix dhcp_agent regression for IPv6 subnet

Changes associated to BugFix:1361545 have caused dnsmasq to be spawned
only for IPv4 subnets. Due to this, dnsmasq is not getting spawned for
IPv6 subnets. This patch addresses the issue.

Closes-Bug:#1382081
Change-Id: I787fd0bc6c90c34ec03a2eff4bd35a754ec188a5

@Dan thanks for this. I made some inline comments, but my biggest issue is whether the service or the shell should be dealing with --os-xxx options.

@Clay, @Sam - any opinions on the following...

Take for example the --os-project-id CLI option.

shell.py parses --os-project-id to option os_project_id. shell.py then copies this to key project_id in a dict os_options.

SwiftService ignores the os_options dict passed from shell and repeats copying os_project_id to project_id in a new os_options dict. NB, SwiftService doesn't know about --os-project-id being a CLI options.

os_options gets passed to the client Connection.

I'm of the opinion that SwiftService should just expect a dict with keys like project_id and not be repeating the stripping of os_ prefix that shell already does.

Alternatively we should strip the dictionary preparation out of shell.py?

Either way, SwiftService should not be creating messages that refer to --os-project-id."}, {'account_id': 13470, 'date': '2014-10-07 09:14:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Replaces Stacktraces with useful error messages.

Changed the message shown when a user doesn't enter project/tenant
id/name to be more informative.

When attempting to stat a container without supplying project/tenant
name or id, an empty response was being returned instead of an error
being raised.

Changed the error raised in swiftclient.client when no tenant or project
is specified to be more specific.

Add tests for basic regression checking.

Closes-Bug: #1372589

Change-Id: I4eb6964d9f1702db119cc0294edc02841b1ecd5f

commit_message:
Add missing dependency to Horizon integration tests

The Horizon integration tests are based on Selenium and require Firefox
to run. Since the browser is not installed by default on the thin nodes
running devstack, add a new macro to do so.

Change-Id: Ie44c36663f8ad9909cf182f852767029b4523a76

[{'created': '2014-10-24 10:44:24.000000000', 'message': 'JSHint job updates

The JSHint job was added during Juno and the style-changes-only patches
that were written to make it pass are unlikely to be backported to the
previous stable branches. Stop running it against stable/icehouse.

Now that the job is passing both on master and stable/juno, it would
make sense to make it voting to keep things that way.

Finally, make sure to update the apt-get cache before installing npm
in order to be more future-proof against future package updates.

Change-Id: I0ff4bad8af7507d039390358bd43df1348ed2e98
'}]
commit_message:
JSHint job updates

The JSHint job was added during Juno and the style-changes-only patches
that were written to make it pass are unlikely to be backported to the
previous stable branches. Stop running it against stable/icehouse.

Now that the job is passing both on master and stable/juno, it would
make sense to make it voting to keep things that way.

Finally, make sure to update the apt-get cache before installing npm
in order to be more future-proof against future package updates.

Change-Id: I0ff4bad8af7507d039390358bd43df1348ed2e98

Are we driving how the code works by how the test was written?  Is reporting the floating IP as DOWN before actually bringing it down the right thing to do?"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-10-23 20:21:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> Are we driving how the code works by how the test was written? Is reporting the floating IP as DOWN before actually bringing it down the right thing to do?

Agreed, this should be an implementation detail though. The test was written with the assumption that, if the FIP is unreachable, then its status is DOWN. This is not the case for the L3 agent implementation. Ideally the two happens within a short span of time and it should be unperceivable; if you look at the current implementation, it can take quite a while between unreachability and the status being down. That said, think about a real-life scenario: the bank or a shop closes its doors and they put the sign up; people may be still inside the branch while the last customers are being served ;P So all in all setting the status down before the work is done seems fairly sensible; in other word I am advertising the world that you should no longer use the FIP as it's being torn down, if I fail then I put it in error.

More details inline"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-10-23 20:23:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-10-23 20:23:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2014-10-23 20:34:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

This is just my view.  Maybe it doesn't match community consensus or anyone else's point of view for that matter.  I'm accustomed to thinking differently than others.  ;)

I would call the "closed" sign on the bank or department store the "nominal state" of the store.  When all of the customers have left and the employees can go home is then the "real status" is closed.

The nominal state of the fip should be set as soon as the API call returns to the caller.  However, the real status of the system lags behind.  It was my impression that this real status was what we were reporting from the agent.  If it isn't then reporting state on the server-side would've been okay too.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-10-23 21:33:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

>The nominal state of the fip should be set as soon as the API call returns to the caller. However, the real status of the system lags behind. It was my impression that this real status was what we were reporting from the agent. 

The DOWN status as reported by the L3 agent (and this might be implementation dependent) means "a) rules processed and b) fip logical resource inactive". Now imagine that between a) and b) the agent dies. The FIP state will stay ACTIVE and yet the FIP doesn't work. Would this be acceptable? Ideally we'd do a) and b) atomically, but we can't unless we rewrite the entire framework.

>If it isn't then reporting state on the server-side would've been okay too.

Doing so can be problematic because the implementation backend may not be reliable, and we may lead clients to believe that the FIP is down, when in fact isn't (see above).

This fix at PS4 does not go deep enough with DVR, so this may need more rounds. That said, what do you suggest we should do? The alternative is to relax the test and design it in a way that it can tolerate a real-life lag that can exist between nominal and real state.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-23 21:36:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:
