Perhaps a more promising course of action here is to relax the Tempest test to allow for some slack in waiting for the status to go from ACTIVE to DOWN. This sounds sensible to me, but I don't understand why the test was not designed this way in the first place."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2014-10-23 22:28:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

>>The nominal state of the fip should be set as soon as the API call returns to the caller. However, the real status of the system lags behind. It was my impression that this real status was what we were reporting from the agent.
> The DOWN status as reported by the L3 agent (and this might be implementation dependent) means "a) rules processed and b) fip logical resource inactive". Now imagine that between a) and b) the agent dies. The FIP state will stay ACTIVE and yet the FIP doesn't work. Would this be acceptable? Ideally we'd do a) and b) atomically, but we can't unless we rewrite the entire framework.

Right, this is still a problem.  Ideally we would do them atomically but I don't see that happening in the short term.  I think I prefer "fip state says ACTIVE and FIP doesn't work" to "fip state says DOWN and yet it works" from a security perspective.  The former is an annoyance to me and the latter would be an unwanted surprise:  I thought I took my instance off of the network but it is still there.

> >If it isn't then reporting state on the server-side would've been okay too.
> Doing so can be problematic because the implementation backend may not be reliable, and we may lead clients to believe that the FIP is down, when in fact isn't (see above).

This is the vary reason I tend toward the current implementation which only reports after it has done the work.  I don't want to "lead clients to believe that the FIP is down, when in fact isn't."

> This fix at PS4 does not go deep enough with DVR, so this may need more rounds. That said, what do you suggest we should do? The alternative is to relax the test and design it in a way that it can tolerate a real-life lag that can exist between nominal and real state.

I guess I think it is reasonable for the test to give the system a little time to report current status.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-10-23 23:14:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

> Right, this is still a problem. Ideally we would do them atomically but I don't see that happening in the short term. I think I prefer "fip state says ACTIVE and FIP doesn't work" to "fip state says DOWN and yet it works" from a security perspective. The former is an annoyance to me and the latter would be an unwanted surprise: I thought I took my instance off of the network but it is still there.

I think they are both undesirable :) security is really not a factor here IMO, assumed we were able to process the rules correctly, state representation becomes a nicety; imo, a client should act on the STATUS change rather than what is observed on the wire, which is supposed to be an outcome of the state transition, not the other way around.

> This is the very reason I tend toward the current implementation which only reports after it has done the work. I don't want to "lead clients to believe that the FIP is down, when in fact isn't."

Well, I remind you of this one:

https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1334926

Current implementation was just as flawed :P'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2014-10-23 23:30:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

> Well, I remind you of this one:
> https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1334926
> Current implementation was just as flawed :P

That was completely different.  That bug happened because the L3 agent was flawed in the way it tore down the fip.  It thought it tore it down but active connections remained.

:P'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-10-23 23:39:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Why do you say it's different? FIP was marked down and yet connections stayed active...you pulling my leg? :O"}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2014-10-24 09:26:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Gents if I may add to this very interesting discussion. I try not to quote too much for brevity but: 

> I think I prefer "fip state says ACTIVE and FIP doesn't work" to "fip state says DOWN and yet it works" from a security perspective. 

indeed (fail-closed vs fail-open for status reporting), but that's not what is proposed here - it would be 'fip state says DOWN and FIP doesn't work' (nominal is 'DOWN' and real still ACTIVE). 

'The test does this too quickly' - indeed, I think this is everyone's first thought but ultimately we are kind of constrained by the published API [1]. For PUT /v2.0/floatingips/?{floatingip_id}? we return 200. So it is OK for the client to have the expectation that the request was completed and successful. They should be able to verify that with a subsequent GET on that resource (which is exactly what the test does). If we ask the test to change, then really we also need to change our API to return 202 here.

I don't like setting the status this way either. But I also don't think we can ask the test to change. Can we explore the agent and status reporting more? From the bug discussion, in one example you can see that the subsequent GET comes 4 seconds after the PUT... that seems like an awfully long time for the nominal and real status yet to be reconciled. I had thought my op reorder would help with the notification but seems it has no effect...

thanks, marios

[1] http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-networking-v2.html#layer3'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2014-10-24 16:59:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Armando Okay, I was thinking from a different perspective.  From an external user's point of view they are essentially the same problem.  I'll take your reference to that bug to mean that you agree with me that we don't want to tell them the fip is DOWN when indeed it is not.

@Marios 

> indeed (fail-closed vs fail-open for status reporting), but that's not what is proposed here - it would be 'fip state says DOWN and FIP doesn't work' (nominal is 'DOWN' and real still ACTIVE).

Right, I agree with you and this is the basis for my objection to this patch.

> For PUT /v2.0/floatingips/?{floatingip_id}? we return 200

You are right but what do we do?  When the API was designed, we didn't even have real status reporting of any kind.  The 200 was thought of as an indication that the nominal state was updated.  One could argue that this was a mistake in the first place to do it this way.  I might agree but I can't change history.

Now, we've added real status reporting but the API remained the same.  Oops.  We're kind of stuck between a rock and a hard place.  So, our options as I see them are:

1) Change the API to return 202

This may be the right long term solution but it isn't an easy change.  We can't just go changing the API willy-nilly.

2) Change the test to allow some lag even though strictly it says 200 OK immediately.  IOW, think of 200 as an indication that nominal status has been updated.

This is my preference for the near term.

3) Let the tests continue to fail

Let's not consider this.  Let's pick either the rock or the hard place and knock it down.

4) Change the implementation so that 200 OK really means it is done.

This is very hard to implement and could add very long wait times to API calls."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2014-10-24 18:16:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Okay, I believe this review page might not be the best forum for discussion as it makes it hard to reply inline. Having said that, my comments below:

Let's not confuse fail-open vs fail-close...they are very different concepts and do not apply here, IMO

I wouldn't change the API either, I don't believe that a 202 is going to address the problem here. The crux of the matter is that the FIP status does not reflect the inherent distributed nature of the operation needed to perform the disassociation. This could be addressed by making the operation transactional; alternatively, we could have a more detailed state machine with a PENDING_DOWN intermediate state that captures the fact that the server processed the request and now it's in the hands of the agent. We would still need fault-recovery in case the server or agent died in flight, but let's not go there.

We could add the extra state, but doing so on the current framework is not worth IMO. Even if we did, the tempest test should need to adjust to follow the transaction ACTIVE -> PENDING_DOWN -> DOWN, and hence it will need to wait."}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2014-10-27 12:21:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Carl:
+1 allow some slack in the test. The error is definitely in the API. From my earlier experiences operations such as 'attach disk drive' etc would never have been a 200 OK... i.e. I would have assumed that such operations wouldn't be effected in the backend immediately and so I'd get a URI I can query (like the URI for the resource itself for example). I'd still argue that we should document this though, so at least it's explicit that when you do a PUT /v2.0/floatingips/?{floatingip_id}? to attach/detach the status for that floating IP may take some time to be seen system-wide. !Docimpact ?

@Armando:
+1 'Pending' - this is exactly how I've seen it done in various APIs, but as you note still doesn't change the timing issue (but it does at least change the expectation of the operation from the point of view of the user/tempest test and in doing so puts the onus on that user/test to verify that status/operation foo was complete). But again, I agree too big of a change and not a priority/worth it now.

Can we all agree that we don't change the API but at least note this on the API operation (PUT)? We can come up with some proper wording."}]

commit_message:
Fix gate failure while checking FIP status transition

*** DO NOT MERGE - NEEDS MORE WORK ***

The tempest test that triggered this failure checks that a FIP
is unreachable before verifying that its status is DOWN, and it
does so without waiting.

The L3 agent logic is  the opposite: the agent destroys the FIP
rules first, and then it sets its status to DOWN. Because of the lag
between the two operations, this may lead the tempest test to
fail intermittently. In the DVR case the failure rate is 100%
because there are more operations involved between FIP rule disposal
and status update.

This patch swaps the operations performed when dealing with disassociated
fips: the agent sets the status first, and then it does the disposal. If
something goes wrong, the fip status will ultimately be ERROR.

Closes-bug: #1381617

Change-Id: I2ad41e7deb33c8037d00364d402b109c3e64a246

commit_message:
Update stevedore base version to 1.1.0

The 1.1.0 release of stevedore fixes a packaging issue that prevents the
documentation from some projects that use stevedore from building.
See Bug #1384919 for more details.

commit_message:
Switch to using pytz>2013

pytz was originally unqualified, but then it was given a version
because of their version scheme being invalid and detected as
a pre-release by pip. However now pytz has PEP 440 valid versions
and tooling is getting stricter still. This new specifier is
now fully PEP 440 compatible.

Change-Id: I4d28a986c7ecb9e1382fa95f70ac9f73cac675ab

commit_message:
Remove running of one Heat test in system test 'Heat HA'

Heat OSTF 'test_autoscaling' is skipped in the HA mode, but in system
tests skipped test equal failed test, it is not correct in current situation.
So need to don't run test 'test_autoscaling' in the HA Heat system test.

This fix was already done in 5.1 in the following commit:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122364/ , but it was accidentally
reverted, so need to add it again.

Change-Id: Ia079ead1ad35c5a65a8139f0dbcd1b4731101dd9
Closes-Bug: #1371025

commit_message:
Update network configuration script

Adds ram and cpu variables, the vcpu variable is commented out. This
will make it easier for users to edit the configuration for network
node.

Consider this a straw man. It's somewhat maximalist, on the principle that it's easier to identify stuff to take out than stuff that should have been copied over but wasn't."}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2014-08-26 08:06:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Thanks Zane, some initial comments inline'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-08-26 08:43:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

See comments inline.

Overall I feel it's a lot of red tape. The TC has to do due diligence on licensing and scope, but I'd be fine letting the programs themselves check that the project behaves properly (reuses openstack components, has review team, etc.)

I think people want the TC less involved, not more involved... so IMHO the TC should just check the critical points (cross-project overlap and licensing issues) that may hurt the project as a whole."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-08-26 14:03:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Since all of our governance documentation currently states projects need a program (either existing or to be created), is this proposal a change to that policy?

Also inline comments.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-09-04 09:54:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Build succeeded.

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/03/116703/1/check/noop/531249e : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-08-25 19:20:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This is the mission statement we've had on the wiki page for the past year, as suggested by Rob Collins in http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-August/014319.html

As a starting point for discussion, I do have a couple of reservations with it myself:

* Our mission is not "to create a service...". Our mission is to change how people interact with infrastructure, and our means may include but are not limited to creating a service, not creating a service, and tearing down a service we already created.
* By claiming the entirety of "lifecycle of infrastructure and applications within OpenStack clouds" we overstate the scope of Heat. Specifically, I think it should be limited to modelling virtual infrastructure (nouns) and not actions (verbs) - I see workflow as a service as outside the scope of Heat.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2014-08-26 21:25:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Do you plan to propose wording that you do like? Because it feels weird to +1 a statement the heat team doesn't like, even if that's what has been documented for a while now. :-)"}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-08-27 14:34:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

TBH I was hoping for suggestions. At the time we discussed it within the team until everyone was thoroughly sick of talking about it and went with the marketing-friendly version that was suggested. I'll raise it at the Heat meeting today and see what the team thinks about it now."}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-08-28 05:17:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

One suggestion inline'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-08-28 09:17:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

You just said you don't want Murano in the orchestration program and the statement has "applications" which thoroughly covers both Murano and Solum. I personally don't mind that scope for the program (delegation ftw).'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-08-28 17:42:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Angus - I agree that's a contradiction (I didn't write the wording of this mission statement). I also don't think we should pre-empt a decision about where Murano/Solum/Mistral should go by claiming the whole application space for Orchestration now (we could, of course expand Orchestration to that scope later).

Do you have a suggestion for improved wording?"}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-08-28 17:49:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I agree that the current wording is broader than what the project is actually doing today, and does intersect with other programs.  I myself would prefer narrow wording, so that a newcomer can tell what is going on where, and the participants have a touch-stone for what is expected of them.  If/when we re-jigger program boundaries then it is natural to re-jigger the mission statements correspondingly.'}, {'account_id': 3098, 'date': '2014-08-28 21:38:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

[{'created': '2014-10-17 00:39:21.000000000', 'message': "Couchbase Root Password Can Go Out Of Sync

if a user goes to the web console of a couchbase instance and adds
another couchbase instance as a server to create a cluster, the root
password for the second server is replaced with the first server's
password (they're synced).

this is problematic because the ping check today relies on the
password in /etc/couchbase/secret_key, which is only set on
prepare(). this means that the status for the second server (and
the third, and etc.) flips to 'shutdown' because the state of the
database cannot be ascertained.

the solution is to retrieve the current password from config.dat for
every ping check.

Change-Id: Ia39b9c57df88b6784d13d8f3fd86967c7cffa743
Closes-Bug: #1380984

commit_message:
Couchbase Root Password Can Go Out Of Sync

if a user goes to the web console of a couchbase instance and adds
another couchbase instance as a server to create a cluster, the root
password for the second server is replaced with the first server's
password (aka they're synced).

this is problematic because the ping check today relies on the
password in /etc/couchbase/secret_key, which is only set on
prepare(). this means that the status for the second server (and
the third, and etc.) flips to 'shutdown' because the state of the
database cannot be ascertained.

the solution is to retrieve the current password from config.dat if
the status check fails with the stored value in secret_key. if the
password parsed from config.dat works, update the stored value in
secret_key.

Change-Id: Ia39b9c57df88b6784d13d8f3fd86967c7cffa743
Closes-Bug: #1380984

I'm not sure we should handle it in this way for stable branches. Shouldn't we instead pin the version to <=2.3 in requirements.txt?

If a distributor is interested in running keystone on fresh python-ldap version, he will be notified about update to requirements.txt file, and if it's needed to run Juno against the fresh library, then he may backport the patch downstream.

That said, I suspect that most platforms interested in Juno already use python-ldap 2.4, so we would probably waste time doing separate backports into each of the distributions. So with my Red Hat on, my vote is +1 (not +2 because I want to hear more from other stable maintainers)."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-10-21 19:20:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-21 19:53:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Use newer python-ldap paging control API

The API for using the LDAP simple paged results control changed
between python-ldap version 2.3 and 2.4. Our current implementation
fails with an AttributeError when trying to use paging with version
2.4 of python-ldap.

This patch detects the capabilities of the underlying python-ldap
version and uses the newer API in versions of python-ldap that have
removed the older API.

Change-Id: I2986e12daea3edf50f299af5927d2a05278e82f7
Closes-bug: #1381768
(cherry picked from commit 1be4a15454e6917571bc937e3bb3589e8f79bc55)

commit_message:
Remove use_namespaces from RouterInfo Property

The use_namespaces property is a property of the agent, not the
router.  The router doesn't need to know if namespaces are in use by
the agent.

Change-Id: I50a1069fc654eeaafaa4098d926ae9e96e5d400f

commit_message:
change default value for s3_store_host

Changing the default value for s3_store_host parameter from
127.0.0.1:8080 to s3.amazonaws.com in glance-api.conf and
glance-cache.conf.

DocImpact: The following parameter is changed in glance-api.conf
and glance-cache.conf.
-s3_store_host = 127.0.0.1:8080
+s3_store_host = s3.amazonaws.com

Change-Id: I39f5bca280b83853021f379c1b7ebe29cff182b9

commit_message:
Remove AltManager class from client

As Change-Id: I280f2b1659c593e14ab9213a161b55bcfc08fa5c has modified
the Manager instantiation for non isolated tenant, AltManager class
is no more needed.

Tests runs for non isolated by instantiating the Manager with 'alt'
credential.

This patch removes the class AltManager from client.py

Closes-Bug: #1329065

Change-Id: I0dcf4050d8524655b017b4b5308fe3070aa2f840

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-09 10:54:45.000000000', 'message': "Test to verify fix to the race when testing error_count

This test attempts to verify the fix applied in the depends-on
review. I have kept it separate because I'm not sure the test
should be merged (it adds idle test time and in extreme is not

commit_message:
Test to verify fix to the race when testing error_count

This test attempts to verify the fix applied in the depends-on
review. I have kept it separate because I'm not sure the test
should be merged (it adds idle test time and in extreme is not
guaranteed to verify there is no race). But it does illustrate
the underlying bug.

I can squash this into the bug fix if reviewers think that is
necessary.

Change-Id: Ia08e67bcd66a5eb84876da60ebf534ba9f3ace20

commit_message:
Fix missing usage of the xml neutron clients

This commit adds a conf check for a use of the neutron xml clients
which is outside of the network api tests. This is causing failures
when the neutron xml api is not available.

Change-Id: I51ca8c5ceb65d4ed07b17ed3c1895eeef1c54878

commit_message:
Move busybox binary-dep to ramdisk element

Busybox should be installed and managed from the ramdisk element,
since that is common to all elements that need busybox.  In
addition, we do not want busybox installed when building Dracut
ramdisks, so it can't be in the deploy-* elements.

Change-Id: I2656d20b466138f7f6dfcf558ba90c6909151d3c

commit_message:
Spelling correction in Installation Guide

The "acontainer-server.conf" expression found in "Install and configure
storage nodes" section in OpenStack Installation Guide for Ubuntu 14.04
has been changed to "container-server.conf".

Change-Id: If5e3a664ef4e42d5e7945364ef5d4b892f38be85
Closes-Bug: #1385070

commit_message:
Cinder api service doesn't handle SIGHUP properly

When SIGHUP signal is sent to cinder-api service, it doesn't complete
processing of all pending requests before terminating all the
processes.

This change is a copy of Abhishek Kekane's fix for nova api.

Change-Id: I049d2aa2f3ad1fe388e00213a71f374803ed409a
Closes-Bug: #1334647
(cherry picked from commit 6c3ad4cf55c5f4cb610fb2625aed1286857b6c67)

commit_message:
Remove `domain` from floating-ip-dns-create-or-update-req body

`domain` is passed in the url req id, so it is unuseful in the
request body, remove it and v3 api-samples.

Change-Id: If8bdfb7fc928daaf01c9612c97c6b391d3139505

commit_message:
Port floating_ip_dns extention to v2.1

This patch ports floating_ip_dns extention from v2 to v2.1,
and have v2 unit test cases shared between v2.1 and v2.
Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ia1316697c141fde2b431ba79aebae5986687a4fa

commit_message:
typo in the policy.json "rule_admin_api"

policy.json has "rule_admin_api" string instead of
the "rule:admin_api" which causes ValueError.

The typo recently introduced by
 4bb34182fe28c89686c8a23ddcfc8e9128d289b5.

Change-Id: I232adfca033e9365927cf2abd62d391337fae429
Closes-Bug: #1385225

[{'created': '2014-10-23 16:43:54.000000000', 'message': "Add ability to deal with migrated volumes

The general migration impl in Cinder works
by creating a new volume, transfering the data
from the original volume to the new volume, and
then deleting the original and flipping the ID
of the new volume.

Turns out we missed the fact that this creates a
mismatch between the volume Cinder will later ask
for and what the volumes identity is on the backend
device.

This change adds a check on create_volume at the drivers
level to see if it's part of a migration and is infact
going to get renamed.  If so, just use the new name
and avoid all the headaches that come later with updating
provider auth and location.

The model info won't change in this case and is accessible
independent of the ID field in the Cinder base and the
crazy change that's going to take place on that value
in the Cinder DB.

Change-Id: If916df5fd986352ffb20f2dd74552e4d7dad4f60
Closes-Bug: #1381943

commit_message:
Fix SolidFire inaccurate model on migrated vols

The general migration impl in Cinder works
by creating a new volume, transfering the data
from the original volume to the new volume, and
then deleting the original and flipping the ID
of the new volume.

Turns out we missed the fact that this creates a
mismatch between the volume Cinder will later ask
for and what the volumes identity is on the backend
device.

This change adds a check on create_volume at the drivers
level to see if it's part of a migration and is infact
going to get renamed.  If so, just use the new name
and avoid all the headaches that come later with updating
provider auth and location.

The model info won't change in this case and is accessible
independent of the ID field in the Cinder base and the
crazy change that's going to take place on that value
in the Cinder DB.

Change-Id: If916df5fd986352ffb20f2dd74552e4d7dad4f60
Closes-Bug: #1381943

commit_message:
Fix the image-build workflow to install dib-utils

dib-utils is needed for images to be built, as well as
for the dsvm-gate tests so we should install dib-utils as
part of both the image-build and dsvm-gate-tests commands.

Change-Id: I4077bb66fb2f20cf26063c456826200ee352df7e

commit_message:
Move to oslo.middlware request_id module

The oslo-incubator request_id module has been deprecated and
removed for kilo, replaced by the request_id from oslo.middleware.

Note that we need to leave the oslo-incubator request_id shim in place
until after Kilo ships, so operators get fair warning about the
backwards-incompatible paste.ini change.

Change-Id: Iedbfede6d57312f565cf4b1ccb71a8418fad8620
Partial-Bug: #1380629

commit_message:
Convert value type in alarm matching_metadata

Commit I0667db868c6f827867a5a20e4a3fa22fcad1a6a1 added query
property in OS::Ceilometer::Alarm resource and add
matching_metadata elements to query list. Value type in
query elements need to be a string, but value type in
matching_metadata elements can not be a string. So we need to
convert value type to string, when we add element to query list.

Change-Id: Ie6af0bfca4f3e089e0ee3e226804a2d365f6d6ae
Closes-bug: #1380168

commit_message:
Remove checking of non empty resp body for 204

In case API respond with 204 status code which mean empty response
body, test case does not need to explicitly check the empty response
body. General check for the same is done in rest_client'
response_checker()

This patch removes those checks of empty response body in tests.

Change-Id: I34537968c1a58e6e73022637a71a3a8091ac214c

commit_message:
CiscoFCSanLookupSerive uses extra argument in init

This patch fixed two issues with the __init__ routine in
CiscoFCSanLookupService:

1. There's an extra argument in super(CiscoFCSanLookupService,
self).__init__(self, **kwargs). It should be changed to
super(CiscoFCSanLookupService, self).__init__(**kwargs).

2. The last line 'self.fabric_configs = ""' should be removed.
self.fabric_configs was created in self.create_configuration() in the
middle of the __init__ routine. It shouldn't be cleared out at the end
of the __init__ routine.

Change-Id: I2623f3b51af34d14849015e52e3676271c9fe414
Closes-Bug: #1385974

commit_message:
Silence tox warning

tox -e genconfig and tox -e pylint both will generate a warning like:
WARNING:test command found but not installed in testenv
  cmd: /bin/bash
  env: /home/aj/vcs/OpenStack/openstack/manila/.tox/genconfig
Maybe forgot to specify a dependency?

Whitelist bash to remove the warning.

Change-Id: Ibab38ce2308760c7089d5d3e298bfc642367e7b4

commit_message:
Prevent AttributeError if no authorization

If you ask client if there is a service catalog when it is unauthorized
it tries to look up the service catalog on a None object. If the client
is unauthorized it should always return False as there cannot be a
service catalog.

Change-Id: I439f71e548b8230e7ce38d1a0e9d0d8f9b205d77
Closes-Bug: 1239219

commit_message:
Build tar with xattr support for Ubuntu Precise

Ubuntu Precise (as used by upstream nodepool currently) lacks a tar
with support for xattr flags.  It's a fairly simple matter to build a
custom version just for precise to work-around this issue.

Tested on Ubuntu Precise creating a centos7 qcow image

Change-Id: Ibae1c642aeec299d236526e652ae6b71d41018a3

commit_message:
Reserve 5 migrations for backports

Reserve 5 migrations incase the need arises to backport any
fixes that require a db migration in stable/juno.

We've never set this up in the past and we did run into a case
last cycle where we had to hack some things around to make it work
without the place holder.

Why 5?  Why not?  For as little as we touch the DB historically
this number should be more than sufficient.

Change-Id: I2830f6557c65c4c9b3056bb5ee72b17346e21823

commit_message:
Add ability to update migration info on backend

The current migration process creates a new volume,
xfr's it's contents, then deletes the original and
modifies the new volume to have the previous ID.

All in all this is kinda troublesome, but regardless
the bigger problem is that the generic impl doesn't
provide any method to tell the backend devices that
their device names/id's have changed.

This patch provides a method to inform backends
that a migration operation has been completed on
their target volume.

It shouldn't be necessary to do anything with the originating
or source volume because it's deleted as part of the process.

Change-Id: Ib5e6a47fe9eedab3e60e77a6c2d987355c0bf167
Closes-Bug: #1383499

commit_message:
Fix a missed argument from a previous refactor

Region name support got changed a little while ago, and a call that
should now be a keyword argument style stayed as a positional ... which
means that we lost region name support for clouds with more than one
region. (it treated all of them like the first region)

Change-Id: I666758a775b8fc8e03b7e9ddd3aa494c13505612

commit_message:
Offload copy_volume_to_image to ceph cluster

Offload rbd's copy_volume_to_image function from host to ceph cluster
could make full use of ceph's inherent data copy feature and the
hardware capacity of ceph storage cluster to expedite the volume data
copy speed, reduce the amount of data transmission and reduce the IO
load on cinder-volume host.

blueprint optimze-rbd-copy-volume-to-image

Change-Id: I5d43c06c3c9a8abde95dec0f8c6cb6c8c6a53e64

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-10 08:51:13.000000000', 'message': 'Cinder Blueprints Support Volume Backup Quota

Since quota take volumes, snapshots and gigabytes into account, it also
needs to take backup into account.
1. Backup create API is not admin interface, users of projects could
create any number of backups.
2. If some evil users create many more big backups to exhaust the free
space of backup storage-backend, it would cause cinder-backup in the state
of rejecting service.

Based on these two points, I think it is necessary to support volume
backup quota.

blueprint support-volume-backup-quota

Change-Id: I8687035f4a1bf50766cc913c5adc20a373e8365d

commit_message:
Support Volume Backup Quota

Since quota take volumes, snapshots and gigabytes into account, it also
needs to take backup into account.

1. Backup create API is not admin
interface, users of projects could create any number of backups.

2. If some evil users create many more big backups to exhaust the free
space of backup storage-backend, it would cause cinder-backup in the
state of rejecting service.

Based on these two points, I think it is necessary to support volume
backup quota.

blueprint support-volume-backup-quota

Change-Id: I8687035f4a1bf50766cc913c5adc20a373e8365d

Remove docutils pin

This was added to work around bug 1091333.  A new sphinx has been
released and so this is no longer necessary.

Also update sphinx requirements from global requirements.

commit_message:
Integrate VMDK driver with oslo.vmware library

The common code between various VMware drivers was moved to the oslo.vmware
library during Icehouse release. The VMDK driver should be updated to use
this library.

Change-Id: I534381608cd6794a5978eb3b41307082cf6a9491
Implements: blueprint vmdk-oslo.vmware

commit_message:
Eventlet green threads not released back to pool

Presently, the wsgi server allows persist connections hence even after
the response is sent to the client, it doesn't close the client socket
connection.
Because of this problem, the green thread is not released back to the pool.

In order to close the client socket connection explicitly after the
response is sent and read successfully by the client, you simply have to
set keepalive to False when you create a wsgi server.

DocImpact:
Added wsgi_keep_alive option (default=True).
In order to maintain the backward compatibility, setting wsgi_keep_alive
as True by default. Recommended is set it to False.

SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1361360
Change-Id: Ic57b2aceb136e8626388cfe4df72b2f47cb0661c

commit_message:
Sync with oslo-incubator

Remove obsoleted modules from tree.
Sync with oslo-incubator at commit
838a2a31fe009feb2501716d6656eeea426ea357.

The updated lockfile module needs setting of the lock_path option,
ensure that it is set in the testsuite.

Closes-Bug: #1382189
Change-Id: I43ca76a21bd5bdb45f23af9b99b96aefa635ccc1

commit_message:
Use oslo.utils

Replace usage of oslo-incubator modules strutils, importutils, timeutils
with corresponding oslo.utils modules instead.
Removes timeutils module, others will be replaced with next oslo-incubator sync.

commit_message:
Cisco N1kv: Remove vmnetwork delete REST call on last port delete

Remove the check for last port delete and subseqeuent call to delete
the vm network. This check was moved to VSM to prevent a race
condition and ensure that the vm network is deleted from the
database when the port count becomes 0.

Change-Id: I6c08a099adfce2fdba8eefec6aadeb68a780ac37
Closes-Bug: 1373547
(cherry picked from commit 4e1c4cbcd71833095534bea9ff7617c582c300d2)

commit_message:
Changing the poll_duration parameter type to int

The poll_duration parameter is defined as a Str in config.py
but while using in code, it is converted to int. So just changing
the type in the config file, so no conversion is required when used

Change-Id: I1d10b4641e3ca8e464258857b27c450a43ad2e87
Closes-Bug:#1332283
(cherry picked from commit 13d55a76d4835f1a436862c7fc0e0af577f26ba5)

commit_message:
Skip lbaas table creation if tables already exist

This patch makes possible upgrade from Grizzly to Icehouse
in case LoadBalancer service plugin was used in Grizzly. LoadBalancer
tables were introduced in Grizzly therefore they necessarily don't
need to be created for Havana and beyond.

This patch goes to Icehouse stable branch only because of all migration
scripts till Havana were squashed together in Juno release. That means
modified file in this patch no longer exists in current master branch.

Change-Id: I09ed3e4b142ccde44cf2e92184d0d92d898a0284
Closes-bug: 1273355

[{'created': '2014-10-09 10:05:28.000000000', 'message': 'Delete DHCP port without DHCP server on a net node

A DHCP-network was deleted from one host using neutron
dhcp-agent-network-remove and then added to another host
using neutron dhcp-agent-network-add command. While the
dhcp-agent-network-remove command was in progress, the
host crashed.  As a result, the removal of the DHCP-network
was partially done. The network was disassociated from
the agent in mysql. However, the agent never made the
release_dhcp_port RPC call to delete the port -- even
after the agent restarted. The end result is that there
are two DHCP ports for the same network. One of these
is found on the host that is no longer hosting the
dhcp-server.

This fix make the DHCP agent invoke the release_dhcp_port
RPC call on a stale network whose dnsmasq process is not
running (not active). Before this change, the RPC call is
made on a stale network only when the dnsmasq process is
running.

Closes-Bug: #1244860
Change-Id: Ie0bafdac698810b5455550c306c6a75ddf91d9bb
(cherry picked from commit 8cf394b896e3644ff51edf6a0d462501fb6e6843)

commit_message:
Delete DHCP port without DHCP server on a net node

A DHCP-network was deleted from one host using neutron
dhcp-agent-network-remove and then added to another host
using neutron dhcp-agent-network-add command. While the
dhcp-agent-network-remove command was in progress, the
host crashed.  As a result, the removal of the DHCP-network
was partially done. The network was disassociated from
the agent in mysql. However, the agent never made the
release_dhcp_port RPC call to delete the port -- even
after the agent restarted. The end result is that there
are two DHCP ports for the same network. One of these
is found on the host that is no longer hosting the
dhcp-server.

This fix make the DHCP agent invoke the release_dhcp_port
RPC call on a stale network whose dnsmasq process is not
running (not active). Before this change, the RPC call is
made on a stale network only when the dnsmasq process is
running.

Closes-Bug: #1244860
Change-Id: Ie0bafdac698810b5455550c306c6a75ddf91d9bb
(cherry picked from commit 8cf394b896e3644ff51edf6a0d462501fb6e6843)

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 13641, 'date': '2014-10-17 20:27:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 13641, 'date': '2014-10-17 20:29:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-17 22:33:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you

commit_message:
Check for IPv6 file before reading

Check to see if the IPv6 disabled flag file exists
before trying to read it. This file doesn't exist
on systems with the IPv6 module blacklisted.

Closes-Bug: #1361542
Change-Id: I4064b4189cc9d8f0f0e0e7025cf6f83d5b6ec276
(cherry picked from commit 0c963f6140237d8d3f361c6aaa7d2a6b656504db)

commit_message:
NSX: Make conn_idle_timeout configurable

If there is a loadbalancer that sits between NSX and neutron usually it has
a default http_timeout on long lived http_connections. This can cause
connections that have not been used from neutron to nsx to be reset after
sometime. This patch makes the amount time we wait to reconnect the connection
configurable so one can set it to match the balancer timeout to avoid having
to try the connection if the loadbalaner has already timed it out.

closes-bug #1382000

Change-Id: Ifca76ca6c24a2002b46b1935fbb4fc63f15c5af1

commit_message:
Update volume-type's quota when extending volume

Now cinder only update total "gigabytes" quota but not update special
volume-type's "gigabytes" quota.

Fix bug #1375120

Change-Id: Ibb0b91afc81ba8c864f3c56fbe8a31972edd9bfc
Signed-off-by: Haomai Wang <haomai@unitedstack.com>

commit_message:
Replacement `_` on `_LE` in all LOG.error

oslo.i18n uses different marker functions to separate the
translatable messages into different catalogs, which the translation
teams can prioritize translating. For details, please refer to:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html#guidelines-for-use-in-openstack

There were not marker fuctions some places in directory network.
This commit makes changes:
* Add missing marker functions
* Use ',' instead of '%' while adding variables to log messages

Change-Id: I5a8f381b6f8fdb4e8febe9e6a901f7cdc6846646

commit_message:
Standardize logging for non-driver parts of nova.virt

 - add log translation hints for warning, error and info levels
 - remove use of % as a string formatter, use the log functionality
   instead
 - move from LOG.warning to LOG.warn

Log translation is motivated by oslo's move to prioritized
translation of strings, as documented at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards#Log_Translation

Change-Id: Ib2a036d782bf3864c820cb47a13687781ef09622

subject: Standardize logging for nova.virt.baremetal

commit_message:
Standardize logging for nova.virt.baremetal

 - add log translation hints for warning, error and info levels
 - remove use of % as a string formatter, use the log functionality
   instead
 - move from LOG.warning to LOG.warn

Log translation is motivated by oslo's move to prioritized
translation of strings, as documented at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards#Log_Translation

Change-Id: If09cda510869034f7538eb4b9e30ac2dd479219c

commit_message:
Add pbr to installation requirements

Add pbr to the list of installation requirements so that it is installed
via pip before this library is installed, instead of with easy_install.
This avoids issues like Bug #1384919, and ensures that projects that use
this library as a dependency are properly installed.

Change-Id: I6c155370dbd01fe4748d5137bdf288e8d3e1a67e

commit_message:
Use oslo.utils - remove importutils usage

Use importutils from olso.utils instead of the deprecated version
from oslo-incubator.

These four files were missed in the previous change "Use oslo.utils"
with id I4f949de57e333832dcc7c1e256ce82e2db0144cb.

Change-Id: I198ea24a0512c60f11caad7cf8ae8c504442026d

commit_message:
Add pbr to installation requirements

Add pbr to the list of installation requirements so that it is installed
via pip before this library is installed, instead of with easy_install.
This avoids issues like Bug #1384919, and ensures that projects that use
this library as a dependency are properly installed.

Change-Id: I6c155370dbd01fe4748d5137bdf288e8d3e1a67e

commit_message:
Pin mccabe to prevent it from breaking hacking

mccabe has undergone some very significant bug fixes recently but has
not yet released a new version. When it does, complexity calculations
will change in potentially significant ways.

Change-Id: I6e75391da19fde45588575517087d1ba4e4c44b7

commit_message:
Add pbr to installation requirements

Add pbr to the list of installation requirements so that it is installed
via pip before this library is installed, instead of with easy_install.
This avoids issues like Bug #1384919, and ensures that projects that use
this library as a dependency are properly installed.

Change-Id: I6c155370dbd01fe4748d5137bdf288e8d3e1a67e

[{'created': '2014-10-23 22:25:23.000000000', 'message': 'Clean up lockutils logging

As discussed in [1], the logging in lockutils is not ideal, both
in terms of clarity and volume.  This change removes some
redundant or just plain unnecessary log messages, while improving
the remaining ones to provide more detail to help debugging
contention issues.  Specifically, it:

 * Adds timing information to external lock messages, similar
   to what was already added for internal locks.
 * Removes a now-unnecessary 'attempting' message that was only
   useful for determining the timing info now included in the log
   message itself.
 * Removes a "released and closed" log message that isn't really
   interesting since it happens after the file was unlocked, and
   only tells us that the file was closed normally, when we would
   only care if that step failed for some reason (which will still
   be logged).
 * Removes the logging in internal_lock that was primarily added
   to debug a phantom problem with eventlet semaphores.
 * Adds a parameter to the lock() context that tells it whether
   to log its debug messages.  This allows synchronized to not
   log duplicate messages when it acquires a lock.

Changes for more intelligent logging, such as only logging when
contention occurs as opposed always, are left as a future
enhancement.

[1]: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-September/047181.html

Partial-Bug: 1374075
Change-Id: I7bb36cdbb2e0f1643e1499054433894142cd2ee3

commit_message:
Clean up lockutils logging

As discussed in [1], the logging in lockutils is not ideal, both
in terms of clarity and volume.  This change removes some
redundant or just plain unnecessary log messages, while improving
the remaining ones to provide more detail to help debugging
contention issues.  Specifically, it:

 * Adds timing information to external lock messages, similar
   to what was already added for internal locks.
 * Removes a now-unnecessary 'attempting' message that was only
   useful for determining the timing info now included in the log
   message itself.
 * Removes a "released and closed" log message that isn't really
   interesting since it happens after the file was unlocked, and
   only tells us that the file was closed normally, when we would
   only care if that step failed for some reason (which will still
   be logged).
 * Removes the logging in internal_lock that was primarily added
   to debug a phantom problem with eventlet semaphores.
 * Adds a parameter to the lock() context that tells it whether
   to log its debug messages.  This allows synchronized to not
   log duplicate messages when it acquires a lock.

Changes for more intelligent logging, such as only logging when
contention occurs as opposed always, are left as a future
enhancement.

[1]: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-September/047181.html

Partial-Bug: 1374075
Change-Id: I7bb36cdbb2e0f1643e1499054433894142cd2ee3

commit_message:
Add deprecated name test case

This is being separated from the change to deprecate the DEFAULT
grouped options because it is exposing a python 3 incompatibility
in oslotest and I don't want to block the release on something this
minor.  Once oslotest is fixed we can merge this to make sure
the deprecated options continue working.

Change-Id: Iabf5ad6ad1e7ad9a426783592f23f58452484b32

commit_message:
Use six.wraps

There is a slight difference in functools.wraps on python3.x and
on python2.x in regards to the __wrapped__ attribute that the six
version makes transparent; so instead of using the functools one
just use the six one to gain the added compatability.

Change-Id: Iccf2aede08504469c148ee5f81f448cadfc08d5e

Move JSON filter unit tests into own file

Separates JSON filter unit tests from test_host_filters.py and refactors
the test methods to remove some cruft.

Change-Id: I31b9b409f4bbc17074067f42ea9da1418d963086

commit_message:
Moves trusted filter unit tests into own file

Breaks out trusted filter unit tests into their own file. In the
process, we remove all DB accesses from the unit tests and uncruft the
unit tests with mock.

Change-Id: Ic895b06a9f6a224f153f12ca5ab54dc8be931f13

commit_message:
Separate filter unit tests for agg extra specs

This patch separates the unit tests for the aggregate instance extra
specs filters out from test_host_filters.py. In the process, it converts
the unit tests to NoDBTestCase and mocks out any database calls.

Change-Id: I7b9f186052825667b585674491d0ddf6b566f8de

commit_message:
Separate compute caps filter unit tests

Pulls the unit tests for compute capabilities filters out of
test_host_filters.py and into their own test file.

commit_message:
Separate image props filter unit tests

Pull the unit tests for the image properties filters out of
test_host_filters.py and uncruft the unnecessary service_up stubouts.

Change-Id: I5d2cd393fd18de9debff424d9ef37e549c2a7ea2

commit_message:
Separate disk filters out from test_host_filters

Simply moves the disk filters out of the test_host_filters.py file and
into their own test file, removing some copy/paste cruft while we're at
it.

Change-Id: I5c83ac1a9fe6c7b6f4019a29d1a5a5847edf1723

commit_message:
Remove warning about management token

Because keystoneclient tries to figure out a management_url in all
contexts, it means that any end-user who uses any python-*client from
OpenStack that is using python-keystoneclient will always get a warning
about not being able to get a management token. This is, however, not
something that they need warning about, since there is no expectation
they'll have one. It's distressing to see it as part of normal
operation.

So just remove the warning.

Change-Id: Ia103a53c09c00fc09cef5fb24be546fc1da0684a

commit_message:
Separate and refactor RAM filter unit tests

The Aggregate RAM filter unit tests were accessing the database to
create Aggregate records. This patch moves all the RAM filter unit tests
out of test_host_filters.py into their own test file and updates the
unit tests to remove any database accesses entirely.

Change-Id: I93399e2af0d230fac9a7f1eb308adfa15e0a84f8

messages:
[{'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-10-21 06:24:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2014-10-21 11:39:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Jay, 

I think it makes sense to make all this chagin in one or maximum 2 patches. 

It's really simple refactoring, and it doesn't require such amount of splitting. 

You are killing gates..."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-10-21 13:36:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Boris, I disagree that I'm killing gates, since nothing has actually gone into the gate yet. Perhaps you are referring to the check queues?

Also, the amount of changes in many of the patches to refactor the unit tests (not just move them out) is substantial. Thus, I think it's better to have a series of <500 LOCC patches so that the reviewers don't have 1000+ LOCC patches to review.

-jay"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-10-21 13:41:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Agree with Jay here, reviewing major refactoring of this kind is much easier when it is split into many small pieces. The gate must be made to cope with what's best for our development process, and splitting changes up into multiple patches is pretty much always a major win for reviewing."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-10-21 13:46:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2014-10-21 14:11:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Let me try to explain my position in more words: 

1) LOC < 500 rule works only in case of refactoring (that changes code, not just splitting code without changes to few modules) or adding new code. 

2) Reviewing 20 patches is more expensive for nova core team (because it requires 40 reviews instead of 2 or 3 for one single patch) 


3) Adding 20 checks + 20 patches in gates (when it is not necessary) is bad, cause this all patches are going to go through gate queue.. 


So overall this can be done in 1-2 patches.. And can be easily reviewed by core team. Which won't produce hell in gates"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-10-21 14:30:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> 2) Reviewing 20 patches is more expensive for nova core team (because it requires 40 reviews instead of 2 or 3 for one single patch) 

This is really wrong / misguided. The number of patches a piece of work is split into is not the primary driver of burden on the reviewers.The complexity or clarity of each patch is what drives the review burden. Is far easier to review this cleanup work as 20 small patches than as 2-3 large patches.'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2014-10-21 14:50:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Daniel, 

I am judging based on my own experience. In this special case, it doesn't help to review. 
 

One more minus is add a lot of noise for people that are using "git log" to understand what happened with project for some period of time..'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-10-21 18:17:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Boris, we will have to agree to disagree on the patch splitting ramifications. :)

I will point out, again, though, that a large number of the patches in this series do not just move code out of a big file into a separate file. The unit tests are refactored to remove database calls and remove use of mox/stubout and fakes in the process, as well as fix subtle bugs in the individual unit tests, as the commit messages for the individual patches explain.

All the best,

-jay'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2014-10-21 20:39:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

I like the change, so I don't want to block it, but I really dislike the approach.."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-21 23:03:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Bump the deprecation version number

These will start to emit deprecation warning messages
in the next version/release (0.6) and not the current
version (0.5) so we should update the messaging to
reflect this.

Change-Id: I8823741847b42056690629fa12c612c8d1ef2cff

commit_message:
Use constants for retry automatically provided kwargs

Instead of using strings use module level constants for
the automatically provided keyword arguments to the retry
revert/execution functions. This makes it easier for users
of taskflow to associate these constants with the actual
keywords, without having to resort to using raw strings
directly.

Change-Id: I739a0ad69819c3ca0d10c98966012cf9ef1b86bd

commit_message:
Use constants for link metadata keys

Instead of using strings (which can be easy to
mistype and get wrong), provide a set of constants
that can be used to attach and use these keys in
flows and at compilation.

This also helps make it more clear what the keys
do and where they are used.

Change-Id: I5283b27617961136a4582bbcfce4617f05e8dd1d

commit_message:
Fix race in shell when testing for errors to raise SysExit

SysExit is raised if the OutputManager has non-zero
error_count. However, error_count is incremented in
a print thread, but tested on the main thread.
Currently error_count is tested before the OutputManager
print threads have exited, which results in a race. This race
means that SysExit is not always raised even when an error
has occured.

This change moves the error_count test after the
OutputManager context manager has exited, which ensures that
the OutputManager threads have exited.

Change-Id: I5ef7d9f10057fe2b41f48ab95066a7265b86a3ac
Closes-Bug: #1379229

commit_message:
Separate and refactor affinity filter tests

The unit tests for the scheduler affinity tests were actually *not*
NoDBTestCase tests. In fact, they were relying on the database to create
instance objects instead of just mocking out the call to
nova.compute.api.get_all(). This patch corrects that and separates out
the affinity filter unit tests out of test_host_filters.py.

Change-Id: Ib7268a49e115fbeff7f18c569cecd82b3d3e8cb3

commit_message:
Can not delete images if db deadlock occurs

Glance api returns 500 Internal Server Error, if db deadlock occurs
in glance-registry for some reason while deleting an image.

Added retry on image_destroy when db deadlock occures which will again
try to delete the image from database.

Closes-bug: 1378215
Change-Id: Ifad403e363daf368e846b5b6838432a7bedbe81a
(cherry picked from commit dae0fa8f1071be41d5541e9a5254abea48f5ba36)

commit_message:
Fix the exception raised when running test by nose

When using nose to run the unittest, Exception
`TypeError: setUp() takes exactly 1 argument` is raised,due to the wrong
place of `@testing.requires_mongodb` decorator.

Change-Id: Idc15fd7b52c7f26b53f0c72af61045f1423548ec

commit_message:
Put a cap on our cyclomatic complexity

flake8 has support for cyclomatic complexity (Mccabe) currently our
worst offender has a complexity of 15 (25 is considered very bad). So
set our max-complexity to 16 so we at least don't make things any worse.

https://github.com/flintwork/mccabe

Change-Id: Ied156f42aaee351f0023ea7dc38bb307ccdbf098

commit_message:
Port update method of cloudpipe_update to v2.1(v3)

This patch adds couldpipe_update's `update` method to cloudpipe controller
add validation schema to cloudpipe, have v2 unit test cases shared between
v2.1 and v2.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ibf39d7fa7301bcba6e259ae88a73c20f64b7fc36

commit_message:
Move the panel mocks to a separate method on TestCase

We need to remove the panel mocks in Tuskar-UI tests, because they
import and register the admin panel as their side effect. To do that
easily, I'm moving that part into a separate method.

Partial-bug: #1384683
Change-Id: Ica366c0b9f680049a74e94007a563ffdb492e4f4

commit_message:
Avoid db lock caused by notification inside db transaction

Some l3-related functions call _update_router_gw_info within
db transaction.

_update_router_gw_info calls create_port() and delete_port()
from core plugin, and the two port-related operations will call
notification which will lead to eventlet yield.

If yield switches a thread to another one that tries to access
the same router object in db we're locked and get db timeout.

The workaround is to make _update_router_gw_info outside of
db transaction.

Related plugins are also updated to reflect the logic.

This bug fix will revert the previous commit:
Pass newly created router to _update_router_gw_info
Change-Id: I7fbbd675839c2874578c62dfed390d86e3b4801a
Commit-Id:06760aff355a4795cec9a17fa330c191cabcfe62

Because _update_router_gw_info is removed out of the transaction,
If we still want to keep the router_db and pass it to
_update_router_gw_info, we need to first merge it.
Here, I prefer retrieve it again from db, rather than merge it.

Change-Id: If24603eac11ea8bd15871a4a0ad9d2bddf829af4
Closes-Bug: #1334109

commit_message:
Fix the example 'default_provides'

The example should be declaring that the whole result is 'a'
and not just the first element of the returned result (which
in this case is the string index[0] which is also 'a') to
avoid propagating bad/broken patterns in the examples.

Fixes bug 1383422

Change-Id: I3a39bb25291276d29ee260e84aab9ec182499fd9

commit_message:
Fix AttributeError when test_function_help fails

This commit fixes a missed usage of the CommandFailed exception during
the migration moving it from tempest.cli to tempest.exceptions in change
Ibf5f1cbbb847d32976b54c4484acfc3c0e3b4f48. The outdated module
path could cause an AttributeError to be raised because the exception no
longer existing in tempest.cli.

commit_message:
Add pbr to installation requirements

Add pbr to the list of installation requirements so that it is installed
via pip before this library is installed, instead of with easy_install.
This avoids issues like Bug #1384919, and ensures that projects that use
this library as a dependency are properly installed.

Change-Id: I6c155370dbd01fe4748d5137bdf288e8d3e1a67e

commit_message:
Porting baremetal_nodes extension to v2.1/v3

This patch ports baremetal-nodes(include baremetal-stat-ext)
to v2.1 and make v2 and v2.1 share unit test cases.

In v2.1/v3,baremetal-nodes will not depend on baremetal-stat-ext.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api
Change-Id: I0f6a968897975ee91e76538d2ce7d2538044613e

commit_message:
Port fixed_ip extention to v2.1

This patch ports fixed_ip extention from v2 to v2.1,
and have v2 unit test cases shared between v2.1 and v2.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api
Change-Id: Ifa7e0dd5a91cfe881077b92aeb7019d0435d780a

commit_message:
Tolerate null on Json db load

A icehouse->juno migration issue has surfaced where
resource.properties_data is null for existing resource records.

This change fixes the Json db type to treat None the same as
the serialized JSON 'null'.

Change-Id: Ia0b9a23a7798c95fbbcba439ffb8203b50367e7c
Closes-Bug: #1383505

commit_message:
Improve lock_path help and documentation

Improve help string to state default value and that it's mandatory.
Document set_defaults function.

DocImpact: Document that the value needs to evaluate to a valid path.
So, either environment variable is set or option is set.

Change-Id: I481d2f8107476ba166a18bc56d3b4c1be5ff726f

commit_message:
Fix server create for boot-from-volume

* server create required --image even when booting the server from a
  volume.  Change options to require either --image or --volume to
  specify the server boot disk.  Using --volume currently uses device
  'vda' for the block mapping and ignores any other block mappings
  given in --block-device-mapping.
* server create and server show are both affected by bug 1378842 where
  an excepion was thrown when no image ID was present in the returned
  server object, which is the case for a server booted from a volume.
* Fix the remaining assertEqual() order problems in test_server.py

Closes-Bug: 1378842
Closes-Bug: 1383338
Change-Id: I5daebf4e50a765d4920088dfead95b6295af6a4d

commit_message:
Remove useless join in nova.virt.vmwareapi.vm_util

This change replaces in nova.virt.vmwareapi.vm_util the pattern
''.join(['fo...o'], ['b...ar']) by the pattern 'fo...ob...ar' which
avoids runtime string concatenation.

Change-Id: If23d8377acde2c3419b67ca11b03a1c898561c77

commit_message:
Merge fileutils from oslo-incubator

We need to get rid of our copy of log.py in oslo.concurrency.

oslo.concurrency code needs fileutils from oslo-incubator.
fileutils needs the common copy of log.py. What happens when we
import oslo.concurrency into nova, we end up with duplicate
options for default_log_levels. So to unravel the knots,
we switch fileutils over to python logging and hence remove
the need for common copy of log.py in oslo.concurrency.

Fixed the import for excutils as well since that change
has already been made in the oslo-incubator copy of fileutils

Closes-Bug: #1385492
Change-Id: I5310bf8a6584ac4f71b607d30b9dae0b12441d41

commit_message:
Update novaclient shell to use shared arguments from Session

The novaclient implemented it's own version of the CLI arguments that
are now provided by keystoneclient's session object. This changeset
converts nova over to utilizing the shared argument registration.

Change-Id: Ifc9ddc08614e28358229db84cb9b54552ca36d51
Co-Authored-By: David Hu <david.hu@hp.com>

commit_message:
Add support to restrict images to certain flavors

Allows support for checking 'flavor_groups' property on images for
flavor group permissions.

Example permissions:

    '!*,ironic' or just 'ironic' -- Only allow image to be used for
                                    'ironic' flavor groups
    '*,!ironic'                  -- Allow image to be used for all
                                    flavors except 'ironic' flavor
                                    groups.

Default for images with no property is '!*'.

Implements: blueprint restrict-image-types

Change-Id: I06373c8bfc572c5448b7f1ef210a3b671c8ab6d8

@Alistair Rather than using interruptable_as_completed you could just collect the future and use:

    f.result(timeout=XXXX)

The problem with that approach is that interruptable_as_completed will keep attempting to get the results beyond the timeout, so you'd also need to introduce retry logic for the single case. The timeout is only really there to allow the operations to be interrupted so that we can kill the client with ctrl-c.

To be honest, strange as it may be, I think that using interruptable_as_completed with a single element list is probably the cleanest option."}, {'account_id': 9216, 'date': '2014-10-07 13:21:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Fix race between container create jobs during upload

During a segmented object upload, attempts are made
to create the container for the manifest and the
segment container. These jobs are currently placed
on separate threads and can occur out of order which
causes the unit test failure seen in the bug report.

The container jobs should be ordered because the
segment container job attempts to HEAD the manifest
container to determine correct storage policy.

This patch enforces ordering of the two jobs and
modifies the unit test to assert that both container
PUTs occur in the expected order.

Change-Id: If90bec126867a4be2df34067ccefee660202f59f
Closes-Bug: #1376878

commit_message:
remove url-path from the default value of s3_store_host

For s3 endpoints, url-path is not necessary to define and it's
something like just "s3.amazonaws.com" for Amazon s3 or
"s3.compatibleserver.com:8080" for S3 thirdparty compatible server
that is listening on 8080. So the current default value with '/v1.0/'
of s3_store_host is confusing.

s3_store_host = 127.0.0.1:8080/v1.0/

DocImpact: The following parameter is changed in glance-api.conf
and glance-cache.conf.
-s3_store_host = 127.0.0.1:8080/v1.0/
+s3_store_host = 127.0.0.1:8080

Change-Id: I3b103121e46f58fda339530c62c71b65a69e5dc5

commit_message:
Cinder api service doesn't handle SIGHUP properly

When SIGHUP signal is sent to cinder-api service, it doesn't complete
processing of all pending requests before terminating all the
processes.

This change is a copy of Abhishek Kekane's fix for nova api.

Change-Id: I049d2aa2f3ad1fe388e00213a71f374803ed409a
Closes-Bug: #1334647
(cherry picked from commit 6c3ad4cf55c5f4cb610fb2625aed1286857b6c67)

commit_message:
Add the Neutron DVR job to the tempest experimental queue

The DVR job is not in the check pipeline for Tempest changes.
This is acceptable for now, as the job is still non voting for
Neutron; however, issues like #1381617 may have been prevented
with some reviewer attention and some CI's aid.

Adding the job to the experimental queue can help with the latter
especially to vet [1] more effectively.

[1] - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/130655/

Change-Id: I9e5148abff804218fa3e16aa7d70b17a6658d78a

oslo.concurrency code needs fileutils from oslo-incubator.
fileutils needs the common copy of log.py. What happens when we

commit_message:
Switch fileutils to use python logging

oslo.concurrency code needs fileutils from oslo-incubator.
fileutils needs the common copy of log.py. What happens when we
import oslo.concurrency into nova, we end up with duplicate
options for default_log_levels. So to unravel the knots,
we switch fileutils over to python logging and hence remove
the need for common copy of log.py in oslo.concurrency.

Change-Id: Ida7ff3418db7c2a0a5e8b827e1c277533812b8ed

commit_message:
Traverse children list to check if any worker stop

Neutron server spawns two green threads for api and rpc job. In
_wait_child, both green threads get pid of the stopped worker from
os.waitpid, but if the pid is not in the green thread's children
list, the stopped worker is not restarted.

Considering this two green threads are in the same process, api
green thread may get a pid belonging to a worker forked by rpc
green thread and will not restart the worker. We need to traverse
the children list of each green thread in _wait_child to ensure
stopped worker can be properly recognized.

Change-Id: I92609fc9d65fe77065b33cf2c8bb36345b7247ac
Closes-Bug: #1384580

commit_message:
Use graduated oslo libraries

The following libraries have been graduated:
- gettextutils -> oslo.i18n
- jsonutils -> oslo.serialization
- strutils, timeutils -> oslo.utils

Add neutronclient.i18n module as oslo.i18n adapter.

Remove openstack.common related files completely
because neutronclient no longer use any oslo-incubator modules.

Closes-Bug: #1382017
Change-Id: Ib7ebcb691a12858049baab3b122f95bf43038f18

Previously, there was a version of mask_password provided by
keystone/openstack/common/log.py. The mask_password function has since
graduated to oslo.utils.strutils and should be used instead. The
mask_password function provided in oslo.utils will handled unicode

commit_message:
Use mask_password from oslo.utils.strutils

Previously, there was a version of mask_password provided by
keystone/openstack/common/log.py. The mask_password function has since
graduated to oslo.utils.strutils and should be used instead. The
mask_password function provided in oslo.utils will handled unicode
issues where as the one provided in oslo-incubator will not.

Change-Id: Icead6e59a624e34c47aafbbe9bdd94eca49d3893
Closes-Bug: #1384409

Adjust some logging levels

* Promote select messages to INFO so lower logging levels can be useful
* Help more modules not say so much all the time

commit_message:
Make diskimage-builder work in Docker.

When running inside a Docker container, we cannot rely on devices in
/dev/mapper to be automagically created by udev, because we probably
don't have a udev at all.  To work around this, run dmsetup mknodes
after every kpartx run.

Change-Id: If7e30579224ce54c5ed26d08974d8293c144719a
